{"title_page": "Peel's Acts", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2019}}\n'''Peel's Acts''' (as they are commonly known) were [[Act of Parliament|Act]]s of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. They consolidated provisions from a large number of earlier [[statutes]] which were then repealed. Their purpose was to simplify the criminal law. The term refers to the [[Home Secretary]] who sponsored them, [[Sir Robert Peel]].  There were two separate sets of broadly identical Acts for England and Ireland respectively.\n\nThe Acts were the product of a failed<ref>No Criminal Code was passed</ref> attempt to [[codification (law)|codify]] the criminal law.  They were replaced by the [[Criminal Law Consolidation Acts 1861]].\n\n==List==\nThe first four Acts on this list consolidated 316 Acts, representing almost four-fifths of all offences.<ref>[http://law.jrank.org/pages/866/Criminal-Law-Reform-England-Legislation-1823-1849.html JRANK]</ref>\n\n===England===\n:The [[Criminal Statutes Repeal Act 1827]] (7 & 8 Geo.4 c.27)\n:The [[Larceny Act 1827]] (7 & 8 Geo.4 c.29) (92 statutes)\n:The [[Malicious Injuries to Property Act 1827]] (7 & 8 Geo.4 c.30) (48 statutes)\n:The [[Offences against the Person Act 1828]] (9 Geo.4 c.31) (56 statutes)\n:The [[Forgery Act 1830]] (11 Geo.4 & 1 Will.4 c.66) (120 statutes)\n\n(The following Act was sponsored (according to law.jrank.org) by Earl Grey and may or may not qualify for inclusion)\n:The [[Coinage Offences Act 1832]] (2 & 3 Will.4 c.34)\n\n===Ireland===\n:(Repeals) (9 Geo.4 c.53)\n:(Larceny) (9 Geo.4 c.55)\n:(Malicious Injuries to Property)(9 Geo.4 c.56)\n:10 Geo 4 c 34,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?pg=PA190&id=5bAuAAAAIAAJ&output=html Google Books]</ref> sometimes referred to as the Offences against the Person (Ireland) Act 1829<ref>Turner (editor). [[Russell on Crime]]. Twelfth Edition. Stevens. 1964. Volume I. Page cxxxiv.</ref><ref>The Irish Jurist, 1968, vol 3, p 150 [https://books.google.com/books?ei=Dt61Uu0YoqrtBva8gYAP&id=H5YvAQAAIAAJ Google Books]</ref> and as the Offences against the Person Act (Ireland) 1829<ref>[[R v Brown]] [1994] 1 AC 212 at 248, (1993) 157 [[Justice of the Peace Reports|JP]] 360, HL, per Lord Lowry [http://www.bailii.org/uk/cases/UKHL/1992/7.html BALII]</ref><ref>86 Journal of the House of Commons [https://books.google.com/books?pg=PA165&id=oB5DAAAAcAAJ&output=html 165]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{English criminal law navbox}}\n{{UK legislation}}\n\n[[Category:English criminal law]]\n[[Category:1861 in British law]]\n[[Category:Robert Peel|Acts]]\n\n{{UK-statute-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2019}}\n'''Peel's Acts''' (as they are commonly known) were [[Act of Parliament|Act]]s of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. They consolidated provisions from a large number of earlier [[statutes]] which were then repealed. Their purpose was to simplify the criminal law. The term refers to the [[Home Secretary]] who sponsored them, [[Sir Robert Peel]].  There were two separate sets of broadly identical Acts for England and Ireland respectively.\n\nThe Acts were the product of a failed<ref>No Criminal Code was passed</ref> attempt to [[codification (law)|codify]] the criminal law.  They were replaced by the [[criminal law consolidation Acts 1861]].\n\n==List==\nThe first four Acts on this list consolidated 316 Acts, representing almost four-fifths of all offences.<ref>[http://law.jrank.org/pages/866/Criminal-Law-Reform-England-Legislation-1823-1849.html JRANK]</ref>\n\n===England===\n:The [[Criminal Statutes Repeal Act 1827]] (7 & 8 Geo.4 c.27)\n:The [[Larceny Act 1827]] (7 & 8 Geo.4 c.29) (92 statutes)\n:The [[Malicious Injuries to Property Act 1827]] (7 & 8 Geo.4 c.30) (48 statutes)\n:The [[Offences against the Person Act 1828]] (9 Geo.4 c.31) (56 statutes)\n:The [[Forgery Act 1830]] (11 Geo.4 & 1 Will.4 c.66) (120 statutes)\n\n(The following Act was sponsored (according to law.jrank.org) by Earl Grey and may or may not qualify for inclusion)\n:The [[Coinage Offences Act 1832]] (2 & 3 Will.4 c.34)\n\n===Ireland===\n:(Repeals) (9 Geo.4 c.53)\n:(Larceny) (9 Geo.4 c.55)\n:(Malicious Injuries to Property)(9 Geo.4 c.56)\n:10 Geo 4 c 34,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?pg=PA190&id=5bAuAAAAIAAJ&output=html Google Books]</ref> sometimes referred to as the Offences against the Person (Ireland) Act 1829<ref>Turner (editor). [[Russell on Crime]]. Twelfth Edition. Stevens. 1964. Volume I. Page cxxxiv.</ref><ref>The Irish Jurist, 1968, vol 3, p 150 [https://books.google.com/books?ei=Dt61Uu0YoqrtBva8gYAP&id=H5YvAQAAIAAJ Google Books]</ref> and as the Offences against the Person Act (Ireland) 1829<ref>[[R v Brown]] [1994] 1 AC 212 at 248, (1993) 157 [[Justice of the Peace Reports|JP]] 360, HL, per Lord Lowry [http://www.bailii.org/uk/cases/UKHL/1992/7.html BALII]</ref><ref>86 Journal of the House of Commons [https://books.google.com/books?pg=PA165&id=oB5DAAAAcAAJ&output=html 165]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{English criminal law navbox}}\n{{UK legislation}}\n\n[[Category:English criminal law]]\n[[Category:1861 in British law]]\n[[Category:Robert Peel|Acts]]\n\n{{UK-statute-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling correction; redirect bypass fromCriminal law consolidation Acts 1861toCriminal Law Consolidation Acts 1861usingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peel%27s_Acts"}
{"title_page": "Abd al Kuri", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox disputed islands\n| plural = \n| name             = Abd al Kuri<br><small>Jasiirada Khuuri</small>\n| image name       = Abd-al-Kuri ISS.jpg\n| image caption    =  Photograph by [[NASA]] astronauts\n| image size       = \n| locator map      = Socotra - Abd Al Kuri.PNG\n| map caption      = \n| map_custom       = \n| native name      = \n| native name link = \n| other_names      = \n| location         = \n| coordinates      = {{coord|12|11|8.9|N|52|14|18|E|source:jawiki|display=inline,title}}\n| archipelago      = [[Socotra Archipelago]]<ref name=\"socotraproject\"/>\n| total islands    = \n| major islands    = \n| area             = 133 square km\n| length           = 36 km\n| width            = 5 km\n| coastline        =\n| highest mount    = Mount \u1e62\u0101li\u1e25<ref name=\"britannica\"/>\n| elevation        = \n| country                         = Yemen\n| country admin divisions title   = [[Governorates of Yemen|Governorate]]\n| country admin divisions         = [[Socotra Governorate]]<ref name=\"NGA\">[http://geonames.nga.mil/ggmagaz/ GeoNames] [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]. Retrieved 3 December 2011.</ref>\n| country admin divisions title 1 =\n| country admin divisions 1       = \n| country admin divisions title 2 =\n| country admin divisions 2       = \n| country capital                 =[[Kilmia]] \n| country administrative centre   = \n| country largest city            = \n| country largest city population = \n| country leader title            = \n| country leader name             = \n| country claim                           = Somalia\n| country claim divisions title           =\n| country claim divisions                 = \n| country claim divisions title 1         =\n| country claim divisions 1               = \n| country claim divisions title 2         =\n| country claim divisions 2               = \n| country claim capital                   = \n| country claim largest city              = \n| country claim largest city population   = \n| country claim leader title              = \n| country  claim leader name              = \n| country 1 claim                         = \n| country 1 claim divisions title         = \n| country 1 claim divisions               = \n| country 1 claim capital                 = \n| country 1 claim largest city            = \n| country 1 claim largest city population = \n| country 1 claim leader title            = \n| country 1 claim leader name             = \n| country 2 claim                         = \n| country 2 claim divisions title         = \n| country 2 claim divisions               = \n| country 2 claim capital                 = \n| country 2 claim largest city            = \n| country 2 claim largest city population = \n| country 2 claim leader title            = \n| country 2 claim leader name             = \n| country 3 claim                         = \n| country 3 claim divisions title         = \n| country 3 claim divisions               = \n| country 3 claim capital                 = \n| country 3 claim largest city            = \n| country 3 claim largest city population = \n| country 3 claim leader title            = \n| country 3 claim leader name             = \n| country 4 claim                         = \n| country 4 claim divisions title         = \n| country 4 claim divisions               = \n| country 4 claim capital                 = \n| country 4 claim largest city            = \n| country 4 claim largest city population = \n| country 4 claim leader title            = \n| country 4 claim leader name             = \n| country 5 claim                         = \n| country 5 claim divisions title         = \n| country 5 claim divisions               = \n| country 5 claim capital                 = \n| country 5 claim largest city            = \n| country 5 claim largest city population = \n| country 5 claim leader title            = \n| country 5 claim leader name             = \n| country 6 claim                         = \n| country 6 claim divisions title         = \n| country 6 claim divisions               = \n| country 6 claim capital                 = \n| country 6 claim largest city            = \n| country 6 claim largest city population = \n| country 6 claim leader title            = \n| country 6 claim leader name             = \n| country 7 claim                         = \n| country 7 claim divisions title         = \n| country 7 claim divisions               = \n| country 7 claim capital                 = \n| country 7 claim largest city            = \n| country 7 claim largest city population = \n| country 7 claim leader title            = \n| country 7 claim leader name             = \n| demonym          = \n| population       = 450<ref name=\"socotraproject\">[http://www.socotraproject.org/index.php?page=content&id=7 Socotra Governance & Biodiversity Project - \"Welcome to Socotra\"] 10-06-2011.</ref>\n| population as of = \n| density          = 3.38\n| ethnic groups    = \n| additional info  =\n}}\n\n'''Abd al Kuri''' ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u0631\u064a}}) is a rocky [[island]] in the [[Guardafui Channel]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Steele|first1=John|title=Ocean Currents: A Derivative of the Encyclopedia of Ocean Sciences|page=160}}</ref> As a part of the Socotra Archipelago<ref name=\"britannica\"/> of the [[Socotra Governorate]] of [[Yemen]],<ref name=\"NGA\"/> it lies about 65 miles (105&nbsp;km) southwest of the island of [[Socotra]].<ref name=\"britannica\"/> It is geographically closer to [[Somalia]].<ref name=\"britannica\">[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1564613/Abd-al-Kuri \"\u02bfAbd al-K\u016br\u012b.\" Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online. Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, 2011.] Web. 6 October 2011.</ref> It consists of [[granite]] and [[diorite]] covered by [[limestone]].<ref name=BA1974>[[#BA1974|Sch\u00fcrmann (1974)]] pp. 24.</ref> There is a dispute between Yemen and Somalia's government over the island's sovereignty.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.yemenpost.net/Detail123456789.aspx?ID=3&SubID=2698 | title=For First Time in History, Somalia Claims Socotra as Its Own | date=27 October 2010 | newspaper=Yemen Post | accessdate=28 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nMuch of Abd al Kuri is semi-desert with little vegetation.<ref name=\"britannica\"/> Two ranges of hills separated near the centre occupy the entire length of the island.<ref name=NM1878>[[#NM1878|Nautical magazine (1878)]] pp. 809.</ref> The northern coast consists mostly of a sandy beach with a few rocky points, while the southern coast consists of steep cliffs.<ref name=NM1878/><ref name=NGA2007>[[#NGA2007|National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency (2007)]] pp. 180.</ref> Its highest point, Mount \u1e62\u0101li\u1e25, reaches an altitude of over {{convert|700|m|abbr=off}}. Most of its inhabitants subsist on fishing.<ref name=\"britannica\"/> Kilmia is the main village.<ref>[http://wikimapia.org/6364535/Abd-al-Kuri-Island Abd al Kuri Island]</ref>\n\n==Flora and fauna==\nAbd al Kuri has a number of [[endemism|endemic]] [[plant]] species<ref name=\"britannica\"/> and an endemic [[bird]], the [[Abd al-Kuri sparrow]] with estimated population of fewer than 1,000.<ref>[http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=32537 Abd al Kuri Sparrow Passer hemileucus]</ref><ref name=\"iucn\">[http://www.iucnredlist.org/apps/redlist/details/181440/0 2010. \"''Passer hemileucus'' \" In: IUCN 2011. IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. Version 2011.1.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923233509/http://www.iucnredlist.org/apps/redlist/details/181440/0 |date=23 September 2011 }} Downloaded on 6 October 2011.</ref><ref name=A&C2009>[[#A&C2009|Redman; Fanshawe; Stevenson (2009)]] pp. 412.</ref>\n\nTwo species of lizards which are native to Abd al Kuri, ''[[Mesalina|Mesalina kuri]]'' and ''[[Pristurus abdelkuri]]'', are named for the island.<ref>Beolens, Bo; Watkins, Michael; Grayson, Michael (2011). ''The Eponym Dictionary of Reptiles''. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press. xiii + 296 pp. {{ISBN|978-1-4214-0135-5}}. (\"Abd el Kuri\", p. 1; \"Kur\", p. 148).</ref><ref>\"''Mesalina kuri'' \". The Reptile Database. www.reptile-database.org.</ref><ref>\"''Pristurus abdelkuri'' \". The Reptile Database. www.reptile-database.org.</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn 1 July 2006, the Somali seafaring vessel ''Mariam IV'' sank off the coast of Abd al Kuri. 16 of the 19 crew members survived, and complications followed when the citizens of Kilmia would not allow the use of their own radio. Rescue by a German helicopter came a week later, but the chief officer was mistakenly left behind. Due to difficulties with wind, transportation, and communication, the officer was not returned to mainland Yemen until September. He described the island as \"A hellish place, where time stands still, and one can feel completely alone in the world.\"\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Native Dwellings, Abd-el-Kuri.jpg|Native dwellings (1903)\nFile:View of the 'Strath' and Native Dwellings, Abd-el-Kuri.jpg|View of the 'Strath' and Native Dwellings, Abd-el-Kuri, 1898\n</gallery>\n==Map==\n[[File:Topographic map of Socotra-en.svg|thumb|600px|center|Topographic map of Socotra archipielago; Abd al-Kuri at bottom left]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{Cite book|author=National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|author-link=National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|year=2007|title= Sailing Directions - Enroute |url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=gQ-7FF8gp5oC|location=|publisher=ProStar Publications|ref=NGA2007}}\n* {{Cite book|year=1878|title= Nautical magazine, Volume 47 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z5AEAAAAQAAJ&dq=abd+al+kuri&source=gbs_navlinks_s|location= London|publisher=Brown, Son, and Ferguson|ref=NM1878}}\n* {{Cite book|author=Redman, Nigel|author2=Fanshawe, John|author3=Stevenson, Terry|year=2009|title= Birds of the Horn of Africa: Ethiopia, Eritrea, Djibouti, Somalia, Socotra |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ofMlZKqOlisC&dq=abd+al+kuri&source=gbs_navlinks_s|location=|publisher=A&C Black|ref=A&C2009}}\n* {{Cite book|author=Sch\u00fcrmann, H. M. E.|year=1974|title= The Pre-cambrian in North Africa |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ws0UAAAAIAAJ&dq=abd+al+kuri&source=gbs_navlinks_s|location=|publisher=Brill Archive|ref=BA1974}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Abd al Kuri}}\n\n{{Islands of Yemen}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of Yemen]]\n[[Category:Socotra archipelago]]\n[[Category:Islands of Somalia]]\n[[Category:Disputed islands]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Yemen]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Somalia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox disputed islands\n| plural = \n| name             = Abd al Kuri<br><small>Jasiirada Khuuri</small>\n| image name       = Abd-al-Kuri ISS.jpg\n| image caption    =  Photograph by [[NASA]] astronauts\n| image size       = \n| locator map      = Socotra - Abd Al Kuri.PNG\n| map caption      = \n| map_custom       = \n| native name      = \n| native name link = \n| other_names      = \n| location         = \n| coordinates      = {{coord|12|11|8.9|N|52|14|18|E|source:jawiki|display=inline,title}}\n| archipelago      = [[Socotra Archipelago]]<ref name=\"socotraproject\"/>\n| total islands    = \n| major islands    = \n| area             = 133 square km\n| length           = 36 km\n| width            = 5 km\n| coastline        =\n| highest mount    = Mount \u1e62\u0101li\u1e25<ref name=\"britannica\"/>\n| elevation        = \n| country                         = Yemen\n| country admin divisions title   = [[Governorates of Yemen|Governorate]]\n| country admin divisions         = [[Socotra Governorate]]<ref name=\"NGA\">[http://geonames.nga.mil/ggmagaz/ GeoNames] [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]. Retrieved 3 December 2011.</ref>\n| country admin divisions title 1 =\n| country admin divisions 1       = \n| country admin divisions title 2 =\n| country admin divisions 2       = \n| country capital                 =[[Kilmia]] \n| country administrative centre   = \n| country largest city            = \n| country largest city population = \n| country leader title            = \n| country leader name             = \n| country claim                           = Somalia\n| country claim divisions title           =\n| country claim divisions                 = \n| country claim divisions title 1         =\n| country claim divisions 1               = \n| country claim divisions title 2         =\n| country claim divisions 2               = \n| country claim capital                   = \n| country claim largest city              = \n| country claim largest city population   = \n| country claim leader title              = \n| country  claim leader name              = \n| country 1 claim                         = \n| country 1 claim divisions title         = \n| country 1 claim divisions               = \n| country 1 claim capital                 = \n| country 1 claim largest city            = \n| country 1 claim largest city population = \n| country 1 claim leader title            = \n| country 1 claim leader name             = \n| country 2 claim                         = \n| country 2 claim divisions title         = \n| country 2 claim divisions               = \n| country 2 claim capital                 = \n| country 2 claim largest city            = \n| country 2 claim largest city population = \n| country 2 claim leader title            = \n| country 2 claim leader name             = \n| country 3 claim                         = \n| country 3 claim divisions title         = \n| country 3 claim divisions               = \n| country 3 claim capital                 = \n| country 3 claim largest city            = \n| country 3 claim largest city population = \n| country 3 claim leader title            = \n| country 3 claim leader name             = \n| country 4 claim                         = \n| country 4 claim divisions title         = \n| country 4 claim divisions               = \n| country 4 claim capital                 = \n| country 4 claim largest city            = \n| country 4 claim largest city population = \n| country 4 claim leader title            = \n| country 4 claim leader name             = \n| country 5 claim                         = \n| country 5 claim divisions title         = \n| country 5 claim divisions               = \n| country 5 claim capital                 = \n| country 5 claim largest city            = \n| country 5 claim largest city population = \n| country 5 claim leader title            = \n| country 5 claim leader name             = \n| country 6 claim                         = \n| country 6 claim divisions title         = \n| country 6 claim divisions               = \n| country 6 claim capital                 = \n| country 6 claim largest city            = \n| country 6 claim largest city population = \n| country 6 claim leader title            = \n| country 6 claim leader name             = \n| country 7 claim                         = \n| country 7 claim divisions title         = \n| country 7 claim divisions               = \n| country 7 claim capital                 = \n| country 7 claim largest city            = \n| country 7 claim largest city population = \n| country 7 claim leader title            = \n| country 7 claim leader name             = \n| demonym          = \n| population       = 450<ref name=\"socotraproject\">[http://www.socotraproject.org/index.php?page=content&id=7 Socotra Governance & Biodiversity Project - \"Welcome to Socotra\"] 10-06-2011.</ref>\n| population as of = \n| density          = 3.38\n| ethnic groups    = \n| additional info  =\n}}\n\n'''Abd al Kuri''' ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u0631\u064a}}) is a rocky [[island]] in the [[Guardafui Channel]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Steele|first1=John|title=Ocean Currents: A Derivative of the Encyclopedia of Ocean Sciences|page=160}}</ref> As a part of the Socotra Archipelago<ref name=\"britannica\"/> of the [[Socotra Governorate]] of [[Yemen]],<ref name=\"NGA\"/>, it lies about 65 miles (105&nbsp;km) southwest of the island of [[Socotra]].<ref name=\"britannica\"/> It is geographically closer to [[Somalia]].<ref name=\"britannica\">[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1564613/Abd-al-Kuri \"\u02bfAbd al-K\u016br\u012b.\" Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online. Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, 2011.] Web. 6 October 2011.</ref> It consists of [[granite]] and [[diorite]] covered by [[limestone]].<ref name=BA1974>[[#BA1974|Sch\u00fcrmann (1974)]] pp. 24.</ref> There is a dispute between Yemen and Somalia's government over the island's sovereignty.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.yemenpost.net/Detail123456789.aspx?ID=3&SubID=2698 | title=For First Time in History, Somalia Claims Socotra as Its Own | date=27 October 2010 | newspaper=Yemen Post | accessdate=28 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nMuch of Abd al Kuri is semi-desert with little vegetation.<ref name=\"britannica\"/> Two ranges of hills separated near the centre occupy the entire length of the island.<ref name=NM1878>[[#NM1878|Nautical magazine (1878)]] pp. 809.</ref> The northern coast consists mostly of a sandy beach with a few rocky points, while the southern coast consists of steep cliffs.<ref name=NM1878/><ref name=NGA2007>[[#NGA2007|National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency (2007)]] pp. 180.</ref> Its highest point, Mount \u1e62\u0101li\u1e25, reaches an altitude of over {{convert|700|m|abbr=off}}. Most of its inhabitants subsist on fishing.<ref name=\"britannica\"/> Kilmia is the main village.<ref>[http://wikimapia.org/6364535/Abd-al-Kuri-Island Abd al Kuri Island]</ref>\n\n==Flora and fauna==\nAbd al Kuri has a number of [[endemism|endemic]] [[plant]] species<ref name=\"britannica\"/> and an endemic [[bird]], the [[Abd al-Kuri sparrow]] with estimated population of fewer than 1,000.<ref>[http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=32537 Abd al Kuri Sparrow Passer hemileucus]</ref><ref name=\"iucn\">[http://www.iucnredlist.org/apps/redlist/details/181440/0 2010. \"''Passer hemileucus'' \" In: IUCN 2011. IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. Version 2011.1.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923233509/http://www.iucnredlist.org/apps/redlist/details/181440/0 |date=23 September 2011 }} Downloaded on 6 October 2011.</ref><ref name=A&C2009>[[#A&C2009|Redman; Fanshawe; Stevenson (2009)]] pp. 412.</ref>\n\nTwo species of lizards which are native to Abd al Kuri, ''[[Mesalina|Mesalina kuri]]'' and ''[[Pristurus abdelkuri]]'', are named for the island.<ref>Beolens, Bo; Watkins, Michael; Grayson, Michael (2011). ''The Eponym Dictionary of Reptiles''. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press. xiii + 296 pp. {{ISBN|978-1-4214-0135-5}}. (\"Abd el Kuri\", p. 1; \"Kur\", p. 148).</ref><ref>\"''Mesalina kuri'' \". The Reptile Database. www.reptile-database.org.</ref><ref>\"''Pristurus abdelkuri'' \". The Reptile Database. www.reptile-database.org.</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn 1 July 2006, the Somali seafaring vessel ''Mariam IV'' sank off the coast of Abd al Kuri. 16 of the 19 crew members survived, and complications followed when the citizens of Kilmia would not allow the use of their own radio. Rescue by a German helicopter came a week later, but the chief officer was mistakenly left behind. Due to difficulties with wind, transportation, and communication, the officer was not returned to mainland Yemen until September. He described the island as \"A hellish place, where time stands still, and one can feel completely alone in the world.\"\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Native Dwellings, Abd-el-Kuri.jpg|Native dwellings (1903)\nFile:View of the 'Strath' and Native Dwellings, Abd-el-Kuri.jpg|View of the 'Strath' and Native Dwellings, Abd-el-Kuri, 1898\n</gallery>\n==Map==\n[[File:Topographic map of Socotra-en.svg|thumb|600px|center|Topographic map of Socotra archipielago; Abd al-Kuri at bottom left]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{Cite book|author=National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|author-link=National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|year=2007|title= Sailing Directions - Enroute |url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=gQ-7FF8gp5oC|location=|publisher=ProStar Publications|ref=NGA2007}}\n* {{Cite book|year=1878|title= Nautical magazine, Volume 47 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z5AEAAAAQAAJ&dq=abd+al+kuri&source=gbs_navlinks_s|location= London|publisher=Brown, Son, and Ferguson|ref=NM1878}}\n* {{Cite book|author=Redman, Nigel|author2=Fanshawe, John|author3=Stevenson, Terry|year=2009|title= Birds of the Horn of Africa: Ethiopia, Eritrea, Djibouti, Somalia, Socotra |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ofMlZKqOlisC&dq=abd+al+kuri&source=gbs_navlinks_s|location=|publisher=A&C Black|ref=A&C2009}}\n* {{Cite book|author=Sch\u00fcrmann, H. M. E.|year=1974|title= The Pre-cambrian in North Africa |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ws0UAAAAIAAJ&dq=abd+al+kuri&source=gbs_navlinks_s|location=|publisher=Brill Archive|ref=BA1974}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Abd al Kuri}}\n\n{{Islands of Yemen}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of Yemen]]\n[[Category:Socotra archipelago]]\n[[Category:Islands of Somalia]]\n[[Category:Disputed islands]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Yemen]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Somalia]]\n", "name_user": "Enrique della Valle", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abd_al_Kuri"}
{"title_page": "Jaguarundi", "text_new": "{{short description|Small wild cat}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Jaguarundi\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |title=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |author=Caso, A. |author2=de Oliveira, T. |author3=Carvajal, S.V. |last-author-amp=yes |page=e.T9948A50653167 |year=2015 |access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n| image = Herpailurus yagouaroundi Jaguarundi ZOO D\u011b\u010d\u00edn.jpg\n| parent_authority = [[Nikolai Severtzov|Severtzov]], 1858\n| taxon = Herpailurus yagouaroundi<ref name=\"Catsg2017\">{{cite journal |author=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O'Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |display-authors=23 |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |issue=Special Issue 11 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref>\n| authority = ([[\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire|Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire]], 1803)\n| synonyms = \n{{collapsible list |bullets=true\n |''Felis yagouaroundi'' <small>Geoffroy, 1803</small>\n |''Puma yaguaroundi''  <small>Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de, 1809</small>\n |''F. eyra'' <small>Fischer, 1814</small>\n |''F. unicolor'' <small>Thraill, 1819</small>\n |''F. cacomitli'' <small>Berlandier, 1859</small>\n |''F. apache'' <small>[[Edgar Alexander Mearns|Mearns]], 1901</small>\n |''F. fossata'' <small>Mearns, 1901</small>\n |''F. panamensis'' <small>[[Joel Asaph Allen|Allen]], 1904</small>\n}}\n| range_map =Jaguarundi distribution.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Distribution of the jaguarundi (2015)<ref name=iucn/>\n}}\nThe '''jaguarundi''' (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'') ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0292|\u00e6|\u0261|w|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u028c|n|d|i}} {{respell|ZHAG|w\u0259|RUN|dee}})<ref>{{MW|jaguarundi}}</ref> or '''eyra''' is a small wild [[felidae|cat]] native to southern [[North America]] and [[South America]]. It tolerates a variety of habitats, and is listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=iucn/> It is a secretive, generalist predator, with a slightly smaller body than [[lynx]]es.<ref name=Simberloff/> Small populations are threatened by human encroachment.<ref name=Texas2003/>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe common name \"jaguarundi\" ([[Brazilian Portuguese]] pronunciation: {{IPA-pt|\u0292\u0250\u0261w\u0250\u027e\u0169\u02c8d\u0292i|}}) comes from the [[Guarani language|Old Guarani]] word ''yaguarundi'', similar to the [[Old Tupi]] word ''yawaum'di''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ferreira |first=A.B.H. |year=1986 |title=Novo Dicion\u00e1rio da L\u00edngua Portuguesa|language=Portuguese |trans-title=New Dictionary of the Portuguese Language |edition=2nd|place=Rio de Janeiro |publisher=Nova Fronteira |page=980}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Merriam-Webster|jaguarundi|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> In some [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-speaking countries, the jaguarundi is also called ''gato colorado'', ''gato moro'', ''le\u00f3n brenero'', ''leoncillo'' and ''tigrillo''.<ref name=iucn/> It is also called ''eyra'', ''gato-mourisco'', ''gato-preto'', ''gato-vermelho'' and ''maracaj\u00e1-preto'' in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=de Miranda |first1=E.E. |last2=Gambarini |first2=A. |title=Natureza, Conserva\u00e7\u00e3o e Cultura: Ensaio sobre a Rela\u00e7\u00e3o do Homem com a Natureza no Brasil |trans-title=Nature, Conservation and Culture: Essay on the Relationship between Man and Nature in Brazil |date=2003 |publisher=Metalivros |location=S\u00e3o Paulo |isbn=9788585371470 |page=113 |language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Nowell |editor1-first=K. |editor2-last=Jackson |editor2-first=P. |editor3-last=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group |title=Wild Cats: Status Survey and Conservation Action Plan |date=1996 |publisher=IUCN |location=Gland |isbn=978-2-8317-0045-8 |page=146}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n''Felis yagouarundi'' was the [[scientific name]] used by [[\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire]] in 1803 who described two [[zoological specimen|specimen]]s from Central America, including one from [[French Guiana]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire, \u00c9. |authorlink=\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire |year=1803 |title=Catalogue des Mammif\u00e8res du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle |trans-title=Catalogue of Mammals of the National Museum of Natural History| language=French |location=Paris |publisher=Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle |page=124 |chapter=Le chat yagouarundi. ''Felis yagouarundi'' (The cat jaguarundi: ''Felis yagouarundi'')|chapter-url={{Google Books|id=951AAAAAcAAJ|page=124|plainurl=yes}} }}</ref> In the 19th and 20th centuries, several more specimens, presumably jaguarundis, were described:\n*''Felis eyra'' proposed by [[Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim]] in 1814 was a [[rust (color)|ferruginous]] skin from [[Paraguay]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Fischer von Waldheim, G. |authorlink=Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim |year=1814 |title=Zoognosia tabulis synopticis illustrata : in usum praelectionum Academiae imperialis medico-chirugicae mosquensis edita |language=Latin |location=Moscow |publisher=Nicolai S. Vsevolozsky |page=228 |chapter=''Felis eyra'' |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/zoognosiatabulis31814fisc/page/228}}</ref>\n\n*[[Gulf Coast Jaguarundi|''F. cacomitli'']] proposed by [[Jean-Louis Berlandier]] in 1859 was a skull and a greyish skin of a female from the [[Rio Grande]] area in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Berlandier, J.-L. |authorlink=Jean-Louis Berlandier |year=1859 |title=Report on the United States and Mexican boundary survey made under the direction of the Secretary of the Interior |volume=II. Mammals of the boundary |editor1=Baird, S. F. |location=Washington |publisher=A.O.P. Nicholson |pages=12\u201313 |chapter=''Felis yagouarundi'' (Desm.) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=TKogAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA2-PA12#v=onepage&f=false}}</ref>\n\n*''F. yagouaroundi tolteca'' proposed by [[Oldfield Thomas]] in 1898 was a skull and a reddish skin from [[Sinaloa]] in Mexico.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas, O. |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas |year=1898 |title=On new mammals from Western Mexico and Lower California |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=7 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=40\u201346 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof711898lond/page/40}}</ref>\n\n*''F. ameghinoi'' proposed by [[Eduardo Ladislao Holmberg]] in 1898 for bones, presumably of a jaguarundi, found near [[San Luis, Argentina]], which are embalmed in the [[Turin Museum of Natural History]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Holmberg, E. L. |authorlink=Eduardo Ladislao Holmberg |year=1898 |chapter=La fauna de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina (The fauna of the Argentine Republic) |pages=477\u2013602 |title=Segundo Censo de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina Mayo 10 de 1895 |trans-title=Second Census of the Argentine Republic May 10, 1895 |volume=1 |editor=Carrasco, G. |publisher=Taller Tipogr\u00e1fico de la Penitenciar\u00eda Nacional |location=Buenos Aires }}</ref>\n\n*''F. fossata'' by [[Edgar Alexander Mearns]] in 1901 was a large skull from [[Yucat\u00e1n]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Mearns, E.A. |authorlink=Edgar Alexander Mearns |year=1901 |title=Two new cats of the eyra group from North America |volume=14 |journal=Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington |pages=149\u2013151 |url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofbio14biol/page/148}}</ref>\n\n*''F. panamensis'' by [[Joel Asaph Allen]] in 1904 was a dusky grey skin of a young adult female collected in Panama's [[Chiriqu\u00ed Province]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Allen, J.A. |authorlink=Joel Asaph Allen |year=1904 |title=Mammals from southern Mexico and Central and South America |journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History |volume=20 |issue=4 |pages=29\u201380 |url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/662//v2/dspace/ingest/pdfSource/bul/B020a04.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref>\n\n*''F. yagouaroundi melantho'' by Oldfield Thomas in 1914 were skulls and blackish brown skins of a male and a female from [[Pozuzo District|Pozuzu]] in Peru.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas, O. |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas|year=1914 |title=On various South-American mammals |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=8 |volume=13 |issue=75 |pages=345\u2013363 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof1319unse/page/350}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Genus (biology)|generic]] name ''Herpailurus'' was proposed by [[Nikolai Severtzov]] in 1858 for the jaguarundi.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Severtzow |first1=M. N. |year=1858 |title=Notice sur la classification multis\u00e9riale des Carnivores, sp\u00e9cialement des F\u00e9lid\u00e9s, et les \u00e9tudes de zoologie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale qui s'y rattachent |trans-title=Notes on the classification of the carnivores, especially the Felidae, and the respective zoological studies |journal=Revue et Magasin de Zoologie Pure et Appliqu\u00e9e |volume=X |language=French| pages=385\u2013396 |url=https://archive.org/stream/revueetmagasinde10soci#page/390/mode/2up}}</ref> Since 2017, the [[IUCN]] Cat Specialist Group considers the jaguarundi as a [[monotypic taxon]] of the genus ''Herpailurus''.<ref name=\"Catsg2017\"/> [[Phylogeography|Phylogeographical]] analysis of jaguarundi samples from across its range found no genetic evidence for subspecies.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Ruiz-Garc\u00eda M. |author2=Pinedo-Castro M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |pages=245\u2013288 |chapter=Population genetics and phylogeographic analyses of the jaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') by means of three mitochondrial markers: The first molecular study of this species |title=Molecular Population Genetics, Evolutionary Biology and Biological Conservation on Neotropical Carnivores |editor1=Ruiz-Garc\u00eda, M. |editor2=Shostell, J. M. |publisher=Nova Publishers |location=New York |isbn=978-1-62417-079-9 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/230597248_Population_genetics_and_phylogeographic_of_the_jaguarundi_Puma_yaguaroundi_by_means_of_three_mitochondrial_markers_the_first_molecular_population_study_of_this_species_Chapter_8_Molecular_Population_G}}</ref>\n\n==Phylogeny and evolution==\n{{cladogram|title=\n|caption=The ''Puma'' lineage of the family [[Felidae]], depicted along with closely related genera.<ref name=\"werdelin\">{{cite book |last1=Werdelin |first1=L. |last2=Yamaguchi |first2=N. |last3=Johnson |first3=W.E. |last4=O'Brien |first4=S.J. |last-author-amp=yes |chapter=Phylogeny and evolution of cats (Felidae) |year=2010 |pages=59\u201382 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266755142 |editor1-last=Macdonald |editor1-first=D.W. |editor2-last=Loveridge |editor2-first=A.J. |title=Biology and Conservation of Wild Felids |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=978-0-19-923445-5 |edition=Reprint}}</ref>\n|1={{clade | style=font-size:90%;line-height:100%;width:450px;\n|1={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |label1=''Lynx'' lineage\n         |1=''[[Lynx (genus)|Lynx]]''\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n         |1={{clade\n            |label1=''Puma'' lineage\n            |1={{clade\n               |label1=''[[Acinonyx]]''\n               |1= ''Acinonyx jubatus'' <br/>([[Cheetah]]) |image1=[[File:Cynailurus guttata - 1818-1842 - Print - Iconographia Zoologica - Special Collections University of Amsterdam - (white background).jpg|80px|left]]\n               |2={{clade\n                  |label1=''[[Puma (genus)|Puma]]''\n                  |1=''Puma concolor'' <br/>([[Cougar]]) |image1=[[File:Felis concolor - 1818-1842 - Print - Iconographia Zoologica - Special Collections University of Amsterdam -(white background).jpg|70px|left]]\n                  |label2='''''Herpailurus'''''&nbsp;\n                  |2=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' <br/>('''Jaguarundi''')\n                  }}\n               }}\n            }}\n         |2={{clade\n            |label1=Domestic cat lineage\n            |1=''[[Felis]]''\n            |label2=Leopard cat lineage\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''[[Otocolobus]]''\n               |2=''[[Prionailurus]]''\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   }}\n}}\n}}\n\nThe jaguarundi is most closely related to the [[cougar]] and [[cheetah]].<ref name=\"Culver\">{{cite journal |author1=Culver, M. |author2=Johnson, W. E. |author3=Pecon-Slattery, J. |author4=O'Brien, S. J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2000 |title=Genomic Ancestry of the American Puma |journal=[[Journal of Heredity]] |volume=91 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013197 |doi=10.1093/jhered/91.3.186 |pmid=10833043 |url-status=dead |url=http://www.coryi.org/Florida_panther/Miscellaneous_Panther_Material/Genomic%20ancestry%20of%20the%20American%20puma.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616200443/http://www.coryi.org/Florida_panther/Miscellaneous_Panther_Material/Genomic%20ancestry%20of%20the%20American%20puma.pdf |archivedate=2007-06-16 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> These three species together form the ''Puma'' lineage, one of the eight lineages of Felidae; the ''Puma'' lineage [[Genetic divergence|diverged]] from the rest 6.7 [[Mya (unit)|mya]]. The [[sister group]] of the ''Puma'' lineage is a [[clade]] of smaller [[Old World]] cats that includes the genera ''[[Felis]]'', ''[[Otocolobus]]'' and ''[[Prionailurus]]''.<ref name=\"werdelin\"/> \n\nThe three species of the ''Puma'' lineage may have had a common ancestor during the [[Miocene]] (roughly 8.25 mya).<ref name=\"adams\">{{cite journal |last1=Adams |first1=D. B. |title=The cheetah: native American |journal=Science |year=1979 |volume=205 |issue=4411 |pages=1155\u20131158 |doi=10.1126/science.205.4411.1155 |pmid=17735054|bibcode=1979Sci...205.1155A |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/6901/86b75e66b681ff0d83772f74068cd1b908b5.pdf }}</ref><ref name=johnson>{{cite journal |pmid=9071018 |year=1997 |last1=Johnson |first1=W. E. |last2=O'Brien |first2=S. J. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Phylogenetic reconstruction of the Felidae using 16S rRNA and NADH-5 mitochondrial genes |volume=44 |issue=S1 |pages=S98\u2013S116 |journal=Journal of Molecular Evolution |doi=10.1007/PL00000060|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1232587 |bibcode=1997JMolE..44S..98J }}</ref> ''Acinonyx'' possibly diverged from the lineage in the Americas;<ref name=Johnson2006>{{cite journal |last1=Johnson |first1=W.E. |last2=Eizirik |first2=E. |last3=Pecon-Slattery |first3=J. |last4=Murphy |first4=W.J. |last5=Antunes |first5=A. |last6=Teeling |first6=E. |last7=O'Brien |first7=S.J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2006 |doi=10.1126/science.1122277 |title=The Late Miocene radiation of modern Felidae: A genetic assessment |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=311 |pages=73\u201377 |pmid=16400146 |issue=5757 |url=https://zenodo.org/record/1230866}}</ref><ref name=dobrynin>{{cite journal |last1=Dobrynin |first1=P. |last2=Liu |first2=S. |last3=Tamazian |first3 = G. |last4=Xiong |first4=Z. |last5=Yurchenko |first5=A. A. |last6=Krasheninnikova |first6=K. |last7=Kliver |first7=S. |last8=Schmidt-K\u00fcntzel |first8=A. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Genomic legacy of the African cheetah, ''Acinonyx jubatus'' |journal=Genome Biology |year=2015 |volume=16 |pages=277 |doi=10.1186/s13059-015-0837-4 |pmid=26653294 |pmc=4676127}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=O\u2019Brien |first1=S. J. |last2=Johnson |first2=W. E. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The evolution of cats |journal=Scientific American |date=2007 |volume=297 |issue=1 |pages=68\u201375 |doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0707-68 |url=http://www.bio-nica.info/biblioteca/O%27brien2007EvolutionCats.pdf}}</ref> some authors alternatively suggest that the cheetah diverged in the [[Old World]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=R. |last=Barnett |author2=I. B. |author3=Phillips, M. J. |author4=Martin, L. D. |author5=Harington, C. R. |author6=Leonard, J. A. |author7=Cooper, A. |year=2005 |title=Evolution of the extinct Sabretooths and the American cheetah-like cat |journal=[[Current Biology]] |volume=15 |issue=15 |pages=R589\u2013R590 |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2005.07.052 |pmid=16085477}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Faurby |first1=S. |last2=Werdelin |first2=L. |last3=Svenning |first3=J. C. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The difference between trivial and scientific names: there were never any true cheetahs in North America |journal=Genome Biology |year=2016 |volume=17 |issue=1 |page=89 |doi=10.1186/s13059-016-0943-y|pmid=27150269 |pmc=4858926}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Puma'' lineage appears to have migrated from Asia to North America after crossing the [[Bering Strait]], arriving in South America via the [[Isthmus of Panama]] by [[Late Pliocene]] or [[Early Pleistocene]]. This was possibly followed by the bifurcation of the lineage into the cougar and ''Herpailurus'' (represented by ''H. pumoides'') in South America around 4\u20133 mya between the [[Late Pliocene]] and [[Early Pleistocene]]. ''H. pumoides'' went extinct around [[Middle Pleistocene]], around the time the modern jaguarundi came into existence; the oldest fossils of the modern jaguarundi date back to the [[Late Pleistocene]] in Brazil (around 0.5 mya). The original North American cougars were extripated during the [[Pleistocene extinctions]] (around 10,000 years ago); then North America was recolonized by South American cougars and jaguarundis 10,000\u20138,000 years back.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Culver |first1=M. |title=Genomic ancestry of the American puma (''Puma concolor'') |journal=Journal of Heredity |date=2000 |volume=91 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013197 |doi=10.1093/jhered/91.3.186}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chimento |first1=N.R. |last2=Dondas |first2=A. |title=First record of ''Puma concolor'' (Mammalia, Felidae) in the Early-Middle Pleistocene of South America |journal=Journal of Mammalian Evolution |date=2017 |volume=25 |issue=3 |pages=381\u2013389 |doi=10.1007/s10914-017-9385-x}}</ref><ref name=bellani/>\n\n==Characteristics==\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| header    = \n| header_align = center\n\n| image1    = Jaguarondi 2.jpg\n| alt1      = \n| width1    = 200\n| caption1  = <center>Red morph</center>\n\n| image2    = Jaguarundi seitlich.jpg\n| alt2      = \n| width2    = 200\n| caption2  = <center>Grey morph</center>\n| background color=;border:none;\n}} \nThe jaguarundi is a medium-sized cat of slender build and uniform coloration that differs significantly from other [[Neotropics|neotropical]] cats in its external appearance. This cat is characterized by several [[mustelid]] features\u2014an elongated body with relatively short legs, a small, narrow head, small, round ears, a short [[snout]] and a long tail. As such, the jaguarundi is sometimes considered similar to [[marten]]s, [[otter]]s or [[weasel]]s.<ref name=\"bellani\">{{cite book |last1=Bellani |first1=G.G. |title=Felines of the World: Discoveries in Taxonomic Classification and History |date=2020 |publisher=Academic Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-12-816503-4 |pages=223-231 |url={{Google Books|id=xK2wDwAAQBAJ|page=223|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref><ref name=\"Nowak\">{{cite book|last1=Nowak|first1=R.M.|title=Walker's Mammals of the World|date=1999|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-0-8018-5789-8|page=818|edition=6th|url={{Google Books|id=T37sFCl43E8C|page=818|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> The head-and-body length is between {{convert|53|and|77|cm|in|abbr=on}}; the strong, muscular tail is {{convert|31|\u2013|52|cm|in|abbr=on}} long. Around twice as large as the domestic cat, the jaguarundi stands {{convert|14|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} at the shoulder and weighs {{convert|3.5|\u2013|7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, though larger individuals weighing around {{convert|9|kg|lb|abbr=on}} have been reported.<ref name=WCoW>{{cite book |author1=Sunquist, M. |author2=Sunquist, F. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2002 |title=Wild Cats of the World |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago |pages=113\u2013119 |isbn= 978-0-226-77999-7 |chapter=Jaguarundi |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/wildcatsofworld00sunq/page/113}}</ref><ref name=\"fws.gov\">{{Cite journal |author1=Brown, D.E. |author2=Gonzalez, C.A. |year=1999 |title=Jaguarundi (''Felis yagouaroundi tolteca'') |url=http://www.fws.gov/southwest/es/Arizona/Documents/Redbook/Jaguarundi%20RB.pdf |journal=Journal of the Arizona-Nevada Academy of Science |issue=32 |pages=155\u2013157}}</ref> Males are slightly larger than females.<ref name=\"bellani\"/>\n\nThe coat is uniformly colored with at most a few faint markings on the face and the belly, though kittens may be spotted for a short duration. Black and white marks on the lips and the snout, similar to those of the cougar, can be clearly seen in juveniles and some adults. The fur color varies from blackish to brownish-grey with a grizzled look due to alternating bright and dark rings on individual hairs (called grey [[Morph (biology)|morph]]), to foxy red to chestnut (called red morph); earlier these morphs were considered two different species. Individuals of both colors can be born in the same litter.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=\"hildyard\">{{cite book |last1=Sirimarco |first1=E. |editor1-last=Hildyard |editor1-first=A. |title=Endangered Wildlife and Plants of the World (Volume 6) |date=2001 |publisher=Marshall Cavendish Co |location=New York |isbn=0-7614-7200-2 |pages=736-738 |chapterurl={{Google Books|plainurl=yes|id=5YYqd4ROFfkC|page=736}} |chapter=Jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yaguarondi cacomitli'')}}</ref> Blackish brown individuals superficially resemble the [[tayra]] (''Eira barbara''), but the latter can be told apart by the clear, yellowish patch on the throat.<ref name=\"ms\">{{cite journal |last1=de Oliveira |first1=T.G. |title=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |journal=Mammalian Species |date=1998 |issue=578 |pages=1-6 |doi=10.2307/3504500 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275737351_Herpailurus_yagouaroundi}}</ref> The red morph is seen more often in dry, open areas. [[Melanism|melanistic]] individuals have been reported, but they are not completely black; the head and the throat are clearly paler than the rest of the body.<ref name=Hunter>{{cite book|last1=Hunter|first1=L.|title=Wild Cats of the World|date=2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1-4729-2285-4|pages=152\u2013156|url={{Google Books|id=hzNBCgAAQBAJ|page=152|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref>  The ears, {{convert|2.5|\u2013|4|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, are widely spaced and, unlike many other felids, lack white spots on the back.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos>{{cite book |editor1-last=Ceballos |editor1-first=G. |title=Mammals of Mexico |publisher=John Hopkins University Press |location=Baltimore |isbn=978-1-4214-0879-8 |pages=498-499 |url={{Google Books|page=498|plainurl=yes|id=UrvxBQAAQBAJ}}}}</ref> The jaguarundi has a total of 30 teeth; the [[dental formula]] is {{DentalFormula|upper=3.1.3.1|lower=3.1.2.1}}.<ref name=\"bellani\"/>\n\nAmong felids, the jaguarundi is closely similar to the [[flat-headed cat]] (''Prionailurus planiceps''), but has a longer body and proportionately longer legs, is heavier and lacks the dark markings on the cheeks of the flat-headed cat.<ref name=ms/> Tawny jaguarundis bear a similar coloration as the signficantly larger cougar.<ref name=Hunter/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe jaguarundi inhabits areas from southern [[Texas]] and coastal [[Mexico]] in the north, through Central and South America east of the Andes, and as far south as northern [[Argentina]].<ref name=iucn/> In 2015, it has also been recorded in [[Cerro Largo Department|Cerro Largo]], [[Uruguay]].<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Grattarola, F. |author2=Hernandez, D. |author3=Duarte, A. |author4=Gaucher, L. |author5=Perazza, G. |display-authors=3 |year=2016 |title=Primer Registro de Yaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') (Mammalia: Carnivora: Felidae) en Uruguay, con comentarios sobre monitereo participativo |journal=Bolet\u00edn de la Sociedad Zool\u00f3gica del Uruguay |volume=25 |issue=1 |pages=85\u221291}}</ref>\nThe jaguarundi has also been sighted around the [[Guiana Space Centre]] in [[French Guiana]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnes.fr/html/_1016_1020_2964_.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041229080857/http://www.cnes.fr/html/_1016_1020_2964_.php |archive-date=2004-12-29 |df=dmy-all |publisher=Centre Spatial Guyanais |title=Un floril\u00e8ge de faune sauvage au CSG}}</ref>\n\nThe jaguarundi inhabits lowland brush areas close to a source of running water, including dry thorn forest to wet [[grassland]]. While commonly inhabiting lowlands, it has been reported at elevations as high as {{convert|3200|m|ft|abbr=on}}. Occasionally it also occurs in dense tropical areas. Their home range is widely variable, depending on the local environment; individuals have been reported as ranging over territories from {{convert|6.8|to|100|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=WCoW/>\n\n===Introduced range===\nJaguarundis have been sighted in [[Florida]] since the early 20th century. Here, the species is assumed to have been [[introduced species|introduced]], but it is not known when the introduction occurred. Their presence in Florida is attributed to a writer from [[Chiefland, Florida|Chiefland]] who at some point imported the animals from their native habitat and released them near his hometown and in other locations across the state.\n\nNo live or dead specimens are known, but many sightings considered credible by biologists have been reported. The earliest of these occurred in 1907, and was followed by various additional sightings throughout the Florida Peninsula from the 1930s through the 1950s. The first official report was released in 1942. Significantly fewer reliable sightings were reported after that, and in 1977 [[W. T. Neill]] concluded the population had declined. However, sightings have continued.<ref name=Simberloff/>\n\nJaguarundis have also been reported in the coastal area of [[Alabama]] since the 1980s, which may be evidence of the Florida population migrating northward.<ref name=Simberloff>{{cite book |title= Strangers in Paradise: Impact and Management of Nonindigenous Species in Florida |last1=Simberloff |first1=D. |authorlink=Daniel Simberloff |author2=Schmitz, D.C. |author3=Brown, T.C. |year=1997|publisher= Island Press |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-1-55963-430-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rtrpSllq4SQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=August 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Behavior and ecology==\nThe jaguarundi is shy and reclusive, and evidently very cautious of [[Animal trapping|traps]].<ref name=Simberloff/> It is generally encountered alone in the wild, suggesting a solitary lifestyle. In captivity, however, it tolerate the close presence of mates. It makes an unusually wide range of vocalisations, including purrs, whistles, yaps, chattering sounds, and even a bird-like chirp. It [[scent mark]]s its territory by scratching the ground or nearby branches, rubbing its head, urination, and leaving faeces uncovered.<ref name=WCoW/>\n\n===Diet===\nThe jaguarundi is primarily [[Diurnality|diurnal]], being active during the day rather than evenings or night. It is comfortable in trees, but prefers to hunt on the ground. It eats almost any small animal it can catch, typically a mixture of [[rodent]]s, small [[reptile]]s, and ground-feeding [[bird]]s. Jaguarundis have been observed to also kill larger prey, such as [[rabbit]]s, and [[opossum]]s; unusual prey include [[fish]] and even [[marmoset]]s. It also consumes a small amount of vegetation and [[arthropod]]s.<ref name=WCoW/>\n\n===Reproduction===\nThe timing of the breeding season among jaguarundis is unclear; they breed all year round. [[Oestrus]] lasts three to five days, marked by the female regularly rolling onto her back and [[spraying urine]]. After a [[gestation]] period of 70 to 75 days, the female gives birth to a litter of one to four kittens in a den constructed in a dense thicket, hollow tree, or similar cover. The kittens are born with spots on their undersides, which disappear as they age. The young are capable of taking solid food at around six weeks, although they begin to play with their mother's food as early as three weeks. Jaguarundis become sexually mature at about two years of age, and have lived for up to 10 years in captivity.<ref name=WCoW/>\n\n==Conservation==\n[[File:Puma yagouaroundi.jpg|thumb|Captive jaguarundi]]\nThe jaguarundi has been listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] since 2002. The megareserves of the [[Amazon Basin]] are probably the only conservation units that can sustain long-term viable populations.<ref name=iucn/>\nIt is not particularly sought after for its [[fur]], but is suffering decline due to loss of habitat. The [[Texas Parks and Wildlife Department]] has expressed concern that its presence in South Texas may be imperiled due to loss of the cat's native habitat.<ref name=Texas2003>{{cite web |url=http://www.tpwd.state.tx.us/landwater/land/habitats/southtx_plain/endangered_species/ |title=Endangered Species |website=Tpwd.state.tx.us |date=2003-04-15 |access-date=2011-09-15 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe North and Central American populations of the jaguarundi are listed in [[CITES Appendix I]]. All the other populations are listed in [[CITES Appendix II]]. The population in Central America is listed as endangered under the [[Endangered Species Act]].<ref name=MSW3>{{MSW3 Wozencraft |id=14000211 |heading=Species ''Puma yagouaroundi'' |page=545}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Acinonychini]]''\n* [[puma (genus)|''Puma'' (genus)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons and category|Puma yagouaroundi|Puma yagouaroundi}}\n{{Wikispecies|Puma yagouaroundi}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=93 |title=Jaguarundi ''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |website=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group}}\n* {{cite web |website=Big Cats Online |url=http://ds.dial.pipex.com/agarman/bco/jundi.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031107150747/http://ds.dial.pipex.com/agarman/bco/jundi.htm |archive-date=2003-11-07 |df=dmy-all |title=Jaguarundi |series=Wild Cat Species and Distribution \u2013 South America}}\n* {{cite Americana |wstitle=Jaguarondi |short=x}}\n\n{{Carnivora|Fe.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q182304}}\n\n[[Category:Puma (genus)]]\n[[Category:Felids of Central America]]\n[[Category:Felids of North America]]\n[[Category:Felids of South America]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Belize]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Mammals of El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Mammals of French Guiana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guatemala]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guyana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Honduras]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Suriname]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Panama]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Peru]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Fauna of northern South America]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Southwestern United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1803]]\n[[Category:Guaran\u00ed words and phrases]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Small wild cat}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Jaguarundi\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |title=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |author=Caso, A. |author2=de Oliveira, T. |author3=Carvajal, S.V. |last-author-amp=yes |page=e.T9948A50653167 |year=2015 |access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n| image = Herpailurus yagouaroundi Jaguarundi ZOO D\u011b\u010d\u00edn.jpg\n| parent_authority = [[Nikolai Severtzov|Severtzov]], 1858\n| taxon = Herpailurus yagouaroundi<ref name=\"Catsg2017\">{{cite journal |author=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O'Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |display-authors=23 |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |issue=Special Issue 11 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref>\n| authority = ([[\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire|Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire]], 1803)\n| synonyms = \n{{collapsible list |bullets=true\n |''Felis yagouaroundi'' <small>Geoffroy, 1803</small>\n |''Puma yaguaroundi''  <small>Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de, 1809</small>\n |''F. eyra'' <small>Fischer, 1814</small>\n |''F. unicolor'' <small>Thraill, 1819</small>\n |''F. cacomitli'' <small>Berlandier, 1859</small>\n |''F. apache'' <small>[[Edgar Alexander Mearns|Mearns]], 1901</small>\n |''F. fossata'' <small>Mearns, 1901</small>\n |''F. panamensis'' <small>[[Joel Asaph Allen|Allen]], 1904</small>\n}}\n| range_map =Jaguarundi distribution.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Distribution of the jaguarundi (2015)<ref name=iucn/>\n}}\nThe '''jaguarundi''' (''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'') ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u0292|\u00e6|\u0261|w|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u028c|n|d|i}} {{respell|ZHAG|w\u0259|RUN|dee}})<ref>{{MW|jaguarundi}}</ref> or '''eyra''' is a small wild [[felidae|cat]] native to southern [[North America]] and [[South America]]. It tolerates a variety of habitats, and is listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=iucn/> It is a secretive, generalist predator, with a slightly smaller body than [[lynx]]es.<ref name=Simberloff/> Small populations are threatened by human encroachment.<ref name=Texas2003/>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe common name \"jaguarundi\" ([[Brazilian Portuguese]] pronunciation: {{IPA-pt|\u0292\u0250\u0261w\u0250\u027e\u0169\u02c8d\u0292i|}}) comes from the [[Guarani language|Old Guarani]] word ''yaguarundi'', similar to the [[Old Tupi]] word ''yawaum'di''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ferreira |first=A.B.H. |year=1986 |title=Novo Dicion\u00e1rio da L\u00edngua Portuguesa|language=Portuguese |trans-title=New Dictionary of the Portuguese Language |edition=2nd|place=Rio de Janeiro |publisher=Nova Fronteira |page=980}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Merriam-Webster|jaguarundi|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> In some [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-speaking countries, the jaguarundi is also called ''gato colorado'', ''gato moro'', ''le\u00f3n brenero'', ''leoncillo'' and ''tigrillo''.<ref name=iucn/> It is also called ''eyra'', ''gato-mourisco'', ''gato-preto'', ''gato-vermelho'' and ''maracaj\u00e1-preto'' in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=de Miranda |first1=E.E. |last2=Gambarini |first2=A. |title=Natureza, Conserva\u00e7\u00e3o e Cultura: Ensaio sobre a Rela\u00e7\u00e3o do Homem com a Natureza no Brasil |trans-title=Nature, Conservation and Culture: Essay on the Relationship between Man and Nature in Brazil |date=2003 |publisher=Metalivros |location=S\u00e3o Paulo |isbn=9788585371470 |page=113 |language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Nowell |editor1-first=K. |editor2-last=Jackson |editor2-first=P. |editor3-last=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group |title=Wild Cats: Status Survey and Conservation Action Plan |date=1996 |publisher=IUCN |location=Gland |isbn=978-2-8317-0045-8 |page=146}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n''Felis yagouarundi'' was the [[scientific name]] used by [[\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire]] in 1803 who described two [[zoological specimen|specimen]]s from Central America, including one from [[French Guiana]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire, \u00c9. |authorlink=\u00c9tienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire |year=1803 |title=Catalogue des Mammif\u00e8res du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle |trans-title=Catalogue of Mammals of the National Museum of Natural History| language=French |location=Paris |publisher=Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle |page=124 |chapter=Le chat yagouarundi. ''Felis yagouarundi'' (The cat jaguarundi: ''Felis yagouarundi'')|chapter-url={{Google Books|id=951AAAAAcAAJ|page=124|plainurl=yes}} }}</ref> In the 19th and 20th centuries, several more specimens, presumably jaguarundis, were described:\n*''Felis eyra'' proposed by [[Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim]] in 1814 was a [[rust (color)|ferruginous]] skin from [[Paraguay]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Fischer von Waldheim, G. |authorlink=Gotthelf Fischer von Waldheim |year=1814 |title=Zoognosia tabulis synopticis illustrata : in usum praelectionum Academiae imperialis medico-chirugicae mosquensis edita |language=Latin |location=Moscow |publisher=Nicolai S. Vsevolozsky |page=228 |chapter=''Felis eyra'' |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/zoognosiatabulis31814fisc/page/228}}</ref>\n\n*[[Gulf Coast Jaguarundi|''F. cacomitli'']] proposed by [[Jean-Louis Berlandier]] in 1859 was a skull and a greyish skin of a female from the [[Rio Grande]] area in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Berlandier, J.-L. |authorlink=Jean-Louis Berlandier |year=1859 |title=Report on the United States and Mexican boundary survey made under the direction of the Secretary of the Interior |volume=II. Mammals of the boundary |editor1=Baird, S. F. |location=Washington |publisher=A.O.P. Nicholson |pages=12\u201313 |chapter=''Felis yagouarundi'' (Desm.) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=TKogAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA2-PA12#v=onepage&f=false}}</ref>\n\n*''F. yagouaroundi tolteca'' proposed by [[Oldfield Thomas]] in 1898 was a skull and a reddish skin from [[Sinaloa]] in Mexico.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas, O. |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas |year=1898 |title=On new mammals from Western Mexico and Lower California |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=7 |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=40\u201346 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof711898lond/page/40}}</ref>\n\n*''F. ameghinoi'' proposed by [[Eduardo Ladislao Holmberg]] in 1898 for bones, presumably of a jaguarundi, found near [[San Luis, Argentina]], which are embalmed in the [[Turin Museum of Natural History]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Holmberg, E. L. |authorlink=Eduardo Ladislao Holmberg |year=1898 |chapter=La fauna de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina (The fauna of the Argentine Republic) |pages=477\u2013602 |title=Segundo Censo de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina Mayo 10 de 1895 |trans-title=Second Census of the Argentine Republic May 10, 1895 |volume=1 |editor=Carrasco, G. |publisher=Taller Tipogr\u00e1fico de la Penitenciar\u00eda Nacional |location=Buenos Aires }}</ref>\n\n*''F. fossata'' by [[Edgar Alexander Mearns]] in 1901 was a large skull from [[Yucat\u00e1n]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Mearns, E.A. |authorlink=Edgar Alexander Mearns |year=1901 |title=Two new cats of the eyra group from North America |volume=14 |journal=Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington |pages=149\u2013151 |url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofbio14biol/page/148}}</ref>\n\n*''F. panamensis'' by [[Joel Asaph Allen]] in 1904 was a dusky grey skin of a young adult female collected in Panama's [[Chiriqu\u00ed Province]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Allen, J.A. |authorlink=Joel Asaph Allen |year=1904 |title=Mammals from southern Mexico and Central and South America |journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History |volume=20 |issue=4 |pages=29\u201380 |url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/662//v2/dspace/ingest/pdfSource/bul/B020a04.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref>\n\n*''F. yagouaroundi melantho'' by Oldfield Thomas in 1914 were skulls and blackish brown skins of a male and a female from [[Pozuzo District|Pozuzu]] in Peru.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas, O. |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas|year=1914 |title=On various South-American mammals |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=8 |volume=13 |issue=75 |pages=345\u2013363 |url=https://archive.org/details/annalsmagazineof1319unse/page/350}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Genus (biology)|generic]] name ''Herpailurus'' was proposed by [[Nikolai Severtzov]] in 1858 for the jaguarundi.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Severtzow |first1=M. N. |year=1858 |title=Notice sur la classification multis\u00e9riale des Carnivores, sp\u00e9cialement des F\u00e9lid\u00e9s, et les \u00e9tudes de zoologie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale qui s'y rattachent |trans-title=Notes on the classification of the carnivores, especially the Felidae, and the respective zoological studies |journal=Revue et Magasin de Zoologie Pure et Appliqu\u00e9e |volume=X |language=French| pages=385\u2013396 |url=https://archive.org/stream/revueetmagasinde10soci#page/390/mode/2up}}</ref> Since 2017, the [[IUCN]] Cat Specialist Group considers the jaguarundi as a [[monotypic taxon]] of the genus ''Herpailurus''.<ref name=\"Catsg2017\"/> [[Phylogeography|Phylogeographical]] analysis of jaguarundi samples from across its range found no genetic evidence for subspecies.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Ruiz-Garc\u00eda M. |author2=Pinedo-Castro M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |pages=245\u2013288 |chapter=Population genetics and phylogeographic analyses of the jaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') by means of three mitochondrial markers: The first molecular study of this species |title=Molecular Population Genetics, Evolutionary Biology and Biological Conservation on Neotropical Carnivores |editor1=Ruiz-Garc\u00eda, M. |editor2=Shostell, J. M. |publisher=Nova Publishers |location=New York |isbn=978-1-62417-079-9 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/230597248_Population_genetics_and_phylogeographic_of_the_jaguarundi_Puma_yaguaroundi_by_means_of_three_mitochondrial_markers_the_first_molecular_population_study_of_this_species_Chapter_8_Molecular_Population_G}}</ref>\n\n==Phylogeny and evolution==\n{{cladogram|title=\n|caption=The ''Puma'' lineage of the family [[Felidae]], depicted along with closely related genera.<ref name=\"werdelin\">{{cite book |last1=Werdelin |first1=L. |last2=Yamaguchi |first2=N. |last3=Johnson |first3=W.E. |last4=O'Brien |first4=S.J. |last-author-amp=yes |chapter=Phylogeny and evolution of cats (Felidae) |year=2010 |pages=59\u201382 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266755142 |editor1-last=Macdonald |editor1-first=D.W. |editor2-last=Loveridge |editor2-first=A.J. |title=Biology and Conservation of Wild Felids |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=978-0-19-923445-5 |edition=Reprint}}</ref>\n|1={{clade | style=font-size:90%;line-height:100%;width:450px;\n|1={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |label1=''Lynx'' lineage\n         |1=''[[Lynx (genus)|Lynx]]''\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n         |1={{clade\n            |label1=''Puma'' lineage\n            |1={{clade\n               |label1=''[[Acinonyx]]''\n               |1= ''Acinonyx jubatus'' <br/>([[Cheetah]]) |image1=[[File:Cynailurus guttata - 1818-1842 - Print - Iconographia Zoologica - Special Collections University of Amsterdam - (white background).jpg|80px|left]]\n               |2={{clade\n                  |label1=''[[Puma (genus)|Puma]]''\n                  |1=''Puma concolor'' <br/>([[Cougar]]) |image1=[[File:Felis concolor - 1818-1842 - Print - Iconographia Zoologica - Special Collections University of Amsterdam -(white background).jpg|70px|left]]\n                  |label2='''''Herpailurus'''''&nbsp;\n                  |2=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' <br/>('''Jaguarundi''')\n                  }}\n               }}\n            }}\n         |2={{clade\n            |label1=Domestic cat lineage\n            |1=''[[Felis]]''\n            |label2=Leopard cat lineage\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''[[Otocolobus]]''\n               |2=''[[Prionailurus]]''\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   }}\n}}\n}}\n\nThe jaguarundi is most closely related to the [[cougar]] and [[cheetah]].<ref name=\"Culver\">{{cite journal |author1=Culver, M. |author2=Johnson, W. E. |author3=Pecon-Slattery, J. |author4=O'Brien, S. J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2000 |title=Genomic Ancestry of the American Puma |journal=[[Journal of Heredity]] |volume=91 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013197 |doi=10.1093/jhered/91.3.186 |pmid=10833043 |url-status=dead |url=http://www.coryi.org/Florida_panther/Miscellaneous_Panther_Material/Genomic%20ancestry%20of%20the%20American%20puma.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616200443/http://www.coryi.org/Florida_panther/Miscellaneous_Panther_Material/Genomic%20ancestry%20of%20the%20American%20puma.pdf |archivedate=2007-06-16 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> These three species together form the ''Puma'' lineage, one of the eight lineages of Felidae; the ''Puma'' lineage [[Genetic divergence|diverged]] from the rest 6.7 [[Mya (unit)|mya]]. The [[sister group]] of the ''Puma'' lineage is a [[clade]] of smaller [[Old World]] cats that includes the genera ''[[Felis]]'', ''[[Otocolobus]]'' and ''[[Prionailurus]]''.<ref name=\"werdelin\"/> \n\nThe three species of the ''Puma'' lineage may have had a common ancestor during the [[Miocene]] (roughly 8.25 mya).<ref name=\"adams\">{{cite journal |last1=Adams |first1=D. B. |title=The cheetah: native American |journal=Science |year=1979 |volume=205 |issue=4411 |pages=1155\u20131158 |doi=10.1126/science.205.4411.1155 |pmid=17735054|bibcode=1979Sci...205.1155A |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/6901/86b75e66b681ff0d83772f74068cd1b908b5.pdf }}</ref><ref name=johnson>{{cite journal |pmid=9071018 |year=1997 |last1=Johnson |first1=W. E. |last2=O'Brien |first2=S. J. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Phylogenetic reconstruction of the Felidae using 16S rRNA and NADH-5 mitochondrial genes |volume=44 |issue=S1 |pages=S98\u2013S116 |journal=Journal of Molecular Evolution |doi=10.1007/PL00000060|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1232587 |bibcode=1997JMolE..44S..98J }}</ref> ''Acinonyx'' possibly diverged from the lineage in the Americas;<ref name=Johnson2006>{{cite journal |last1=Johnson |first1=W.E. |last2=Eizirik |first2=E. |last3=Pecon-Slattery |first3=J. |last4=Murphy |first4=W.J. |last5=Antunes |first5=A. |last6=Teeling |first6=E. |last7=O'Brien |first7=S.J. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2006 |doi=10.1126/science.1122277 |title=The Late Miocene radiation of modern Felidae: A genetic assessment |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=311 |pages=73\u201377 |pmid=16400146 |issue=5757 |url=https://zenodo.org/record/1230866}}</ref><ref name=dobrynin>{{cite journal |last1=Dobrynin |first1=P. |last2=Liu |first2=S. |last3=Tamazian |first3 = G. |last4=Xiong |first4=Z. |last5=Yurchenko |first5=A. A. |last6=Krasheninnikova |first6=K. |last7=Kliver |first7=S. |last8=Schmidt-K\u00fcntzel |first8=A. |last-author-amp=yes |title=Genomic legacy of the African cheetah, ''Acinonyx jubatus'' |journal=Genome Biology |year=2015 |volume=16 |pages=277 |doi=10.1186/s13059-015-0837-4 |pmid=26653294 |pmc=4676127}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=O\u2019Brien |first1=S. J. |last2=Johnson |first2=W. E. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The evolution of cats |journal=Scientific American |date=2007 |volume=297 |issue=1 |pages=68\u201375 |doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0707-68 |url=http://www.bio-nica.info/biblioteca/O%27brien2007EvolutionCats.pdf}}</ref> some authors alternatively suggest that the cheetah diverged in the [[Old World]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=R. |last=Barnett |author2=I. B. |author3=Phillips, M. J. |author4=Martin, L. D. |author5=Harington, C. R. |author6=Leonard, J. A. |author7=Cooper, A. |year=2005 |title=Evolution of the extinct Sabretooths and the American cheetah-like cat |journal=[[Current Biology]] |volume=15 |issue=15 |pages=R589\u2013R590 |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2005.07.052 |pmid=16085477}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Faurby |first1=S. |last2=Werdelin |first2=L. |last3=Svenning |first3=J. C. |last-author-amp=yes |title=The difference between trivial and scientific names: there were never any true cheetahs in North America |journal=Genome Biology |year=2016 |volume=17 |issue=1 |page=89 |doi=10.1186/s13059-016-0943-y|pmid=27150269 |pmc=4858926}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Puma'' lineage appears to have migrated from Asia to North America after crossing the [[Bering Strait]], arriving in South America via the [[Isthmus of Panama]] by [[Late Pliocene]] or [[Early Pleistocene]]. This was possibly followed by the bifurcation of the lineage into the cougar and ''Herpailurus'' (represented by ''H. pumoides'') in South America around 3\u20134 mya between the [[Late Pliocene]] and [[Early Pleistocene]]. ''H. pumoides'' went extinct around [[Middle Pleistocene]], around the time the modern jaguarundi came into existence; the oldest fossils of the modern jaguarundi date back to the [[Late Pleistocene]] in Brazil (around 0.5 mya). The original North American cougars were extripated during the [[Pleistocene extinctions]] (around 10,000 years ago); then North America was recolonized by South American cougars and jaguarundis 10,000\u20138,000 years back.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Culver |first1=M. |title=Genomic ancestry of the American puma (''Puma concolor'') |journal=Journal of Heredity |date=2000 |volume=91 |issue=3 |pages=186\u2013197 |doi=10.1093/jhered/91.3.186}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chimento |first1=N.R. |last2=Dondas |first2=A. |title=First record of ''Puma concolor'' (Mammalia, Felidae) in the Early-Middle Pleistocene of South America |journal=Journal of Mammalian Evolution |date=2017 |volume=25 |issue=3 |pages=381\u2013389 |doi=10.1007/s10914-017-9385-x}}</ref><ref name=bellani/>\n\n==Characteristics==\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| header    = \n| header_align = center\n\n| image1    = Jaguarondi 2.jpg\n| alt1      = \n| width1    = 200\n| caption1  = <center>Red morph</center>\n\n| image2    = Jaguarundi seitlich.jpg\n| alt2      = \n| width2    = 200\n| caption2  = <center>Grey morph</center>\n| background color=;border:none;\n}} \nThe jaguarundi is a medium-sized cat of slender build and uniform coloration that differs significantly from other [[Neotropics|neotropical]] cats in its external appearance. This cat is characterized by several [[mustelid]] features\u2014an elongated body with relatively short legs, a small, narrow head, small, round ears, a short [[snout]] and a long tail. As such, the jaguarundi is sometimes considered similar to [[marten]]s, [[otter]]s or [[weasel]]s.<ref name=\"bellani\">{{cite book |last1=Bellani |first1=G.G. |title=Felines of the World: Discoveries in Taxonomic Classification and History |date=2020 |publisher=Academic Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-12-816503-4 |pages=223-231 |url={{Google Books|id=xK2wDwAAQBAJ|page=223|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref><ref name=\"Nowak\">{{cite book|last1=Nowak|first1=R.M.|title=Walker's Mammals of the World|date=1999|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-0-8018-5789-8|page=818|edition=6th|url={{Google Books|id=T37sFCl43E8C|page=818|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> The head-and-body length is between {{convert|53|and|77|cm|in|abbr=on}}; the strong, muscular tail is {{convert|31|\u2013|52|cm|in|abbr=on}} long. Around twice as large as the domestic cat, the jaguarundi stands {{convert|14|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} at the shoulder and weighs {{convert|3.5|\u2013|7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, though larger individuals weighing around {{convert|9|kg|lb|abbr=on}} have been reported.<ref name=WCoW>{{cite book |author1=Sunquist, M. |author2=Sunquist, F. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2002 |title=Wild Cats of the World |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago |pages=113\u2013119 |isbn= 978-0-226-77999-7 |chapter=Jaguarundi |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/wildcatsofworld00sunq/page/113}}</ref><ref name=\"fws.gov\">{{Cite journal |author1=Brown, D.E. |author2=Gonzalez, C.A. |year=1999 |title=Jaguarundi (''Felis yagouaroundi tolteca'') |url=http://www.fws.gov/southwest/es/Arizona/Documents/Redbook/Jaguarundi%20RB.pdf |journal=Journal of the Arizona-Nevada Academy of Science |issue=32 |pages=155\u2013157}}</ref> Males are slightly larger than females.<ref name=\"bellani\"/>\n\nThe coat is uniformly colored with at most a few faint markings on the face and the belly, though kittens may be spotted for a short duration. Black and white marks on the lips and the snout, similar to those of the cougar, can be clearly seen in juveniles and some adults. The fur color varies from blackish to brownish-grey with a grizzled look due to alternating bright and dark rings on individual hairs (called grey [[Morph (biology)|morph]]), to foxy red to chestnut (called red morph); earlier these morphs were considered two different species. Individuals of both colors can be born in the same litter.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=\"hildyard\">{{cite book |last1=Sirimarco |first1=E. |editor1-last=Hildyard |editor1-first=A. |title=Endangered Wildlife and Plants of the World (Volume 6) |date=2001 |publisher=Marshall Cavendish Co |location=New York |isbn=0-7614-7200-2 |pages=736-738 |chapterurl={{Google Books|plainurl=yes|id=5YYqd4ROFfkC|page=736}} |chapter=Jaguarundi (''Herpailurus yaguarondi cacomitli'')}}</ref> Blackish brown individuals superficially resemble the [[tayra]] (''Eira barbara''), but the latter can be told apart by the clear, yellowish patch on the throat.<ref name=\"ms\">{{cite journal |last1=de Oliveira |first1=T.G. |title=''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |journal=Mammalian Species |date=1998 |issue=578 |pages=1-6 |doi=10.2307/3504500 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275737351_Herpailurus_yagouaroundi}}</ref> The red morph is seen more often in dry, open areas. [[Melanism|melanistic]] individuals have been reported, but they are not completely black; the head and the throat are clearly paler than the rest of the body.<ref name=Hunter>{{cite book|last1=Hunter|first1=L.|title=Wild Cats of the World|date=2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1-4729-2285-4|pages=152\u2013156|url={{Google Books|id=hzNBCgAAQBAJ|page=152|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref>  The ears, {{convert|2.5|\u2013|4|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, are widely spaced and, unlike many other felids, lack white spots on the back.<ref name=WCoW/><ref name=ceballos>{{cite book |editor1-last=Ceballos |editor1-first=G. |title=Mammals of Mexico |publisher=John Hopkins University Press |location=Baltimore |isbn=978-1-4214-0879-8 |pages=498-499 |url={{Google Books|page=498|plainurl=yes|id=UrvxBQAAQBAJ}}}}</ref> The jaguarundi has a total of 30 teeth; the [[dental formula]] is {{DentalFormula|upper=3.1.3.1|lower=3.1.2.1}}.<ref name=\"bellani\"/>\n\nAmong felids, the jaguarundi is closely similar to the [[flat-headed cat]] (''Prionailurus planiceps''), but has a longer body and proportionately longer legs, is heavier and lacks the dark markings on the cheeks of the flat-headed cat.<ref name=ms/> Tawny jaguarundis bear a similar coloration as the signficantly larger cougar.<ref name=Hunter/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe jaguarundi inhabits areas from southern [[Texas]] and coastal [[Mexico]] in the north, through Central and South America east of the Andes, and as far south as northern [[Argentina]].<ref name=iucn/> In 2015, it has also been recorded in [[Cerro Largo Department|Cerro Largo]], [[Uruguay]].<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Grattarola, F. |author2=Hernandez, D. |author3=Duarte, A. |author4=Gaucher, L. |author5=Perazza, G. |display-authors=3 |year=2016 |title=Primer Registro de Yaguarundi (''Puma yagouaroundi'') (Mammalia: Carnivora: Felidae) en Uruguay, con comentarios sobre monitereo participativo |journal=Bolet\u00edn de la Sociedad Zool\u00f3gica del Uruguay |volume=25 |issue=1 |pages=85\u221291}}</ref>\nThe jaguarundi has also been sighted around the [[Guiana Space Centre]] in [[French Guiana]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnes.fr/html/_1016_1020_2964_.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041229080857/http://www.cnes.fr/html/_1016_1020_2964_.php |archive-date=2004-12-29 |df=dmy-all |publisher=Centre Spatial Guyanais |title=Un floril\u00e8ge de faune sauvage au CSG}}</ref>\n\nThe jaguarundi inhabits lowland brush areas close to a source of running water, including dry thorn forest to wet [[grassland]]. While commonly inhabiting lowlands, it has been reported at elevations as high as {{convert|3200|m|ft|abbr=on}}. Occasionally it also occurs in dense tropical areas. Their home range is widely variable, depending on the local environment; individuals have been reported as ranging over territories from {{convert|6.8|to|100|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=WCoW/>\n\n===Introduced range===\nJaguarundis have been sighted in [[Florida]] since the early 20th century. Here, the species is assumed to have been [[introduced species|introduced]], but it is not known when the introduction occurred. Their presence in Florida is attributed to a writer from [[Chiefland, Florida|Chiefland]] who at some point imported the animals from their native habitat and released them near his hometown and in other locations across the state.\n\nNo live or dead specimens are known, but many sightings considered credible by biologists have been reported. The earliest of these occurred in 1907, and was followed by various additional sightings throughout the Florida Peninsula from the 1930s through the 1950s. The first official report was released in 1942. Significantly fewer reliable sightings were reported after that, and in 1977 [[W. T. Neill]] concluded the population had declined. However, sightings have continued.<ref name=Simberloff/>\n\nJaguarundis have also been reported in the coastal area of [[Alabama]] since the 1980s, which may be evidence of the Florida population migrating northward.<ref name=Simberloff>{{cite book |title= Strangers in Paradise: Impact and Management of Nonindigenous Species in Florida |last1=Simberloff |first1=D. |authorlink=Daniel Simberloff |author2=Schmitz, D.C. |author3=Brown, T.C. |year=1997|publisher= Island Press |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-1-55963-430-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rtrpSllq4SQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=August 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Behavior and ecology==\nThe jaguarundi is shy and reclusive, and evidently very cautious of [[Animal trapping|traps]].<ref name=Simberloff/> It is generally encountered alone in the wild, suggesting a solitary lifestyle. In captivity, however, it tolerate the close presence of mates. It makes an unusually wide range of vocalisations, including purrs, whistles, yaps, chattering sounds, and even a bird-like chirp. It [[scent mark]]s its territory by scratching the ground or nearby branches, rubbing its head, urination, and leaving faeces uncovered.<ref name=WCoW/>\n\n===Diet===\nThe jaguarundi is primarily [[Diurnality|diurnal]], being active during the day rather than evenings or night. It is comfortable in trees, but prefers to hunt on the ground. It eats almost any small animal it can catch, typically a mixture of [[rodent]]s, small [[reptile]]s, and ground-feeding [[bird]]s. Jaguarundis have been observed to also kill larger prey, such as [[rabbit]]s, and [[opossum]]s; unusual prey include [[fish]] and even [[marmoset]]s. It also consumes a small amount of vegetation and [[arthropod]]s.<ref name=WCoW/>\n\n===Reproduction===\nThe timing of the breeding season among jaguarundis is unclear; they breed all year round. [[Oestrus]] lasts three to five days, marked by the female regularly rolling onto her back and [[spraying urine]]. After a [[gestation]] period of 70 to 75 days, the female gives birth to a litter of one to four kittens in a den constructed in a dense thicket, hollow tree, or similar cover. The kittens are born with spots on their undersides, which disappear as they age. The young are capable of taking solid food at around six weeks, although they begin to play with their mother's food as early as three weeks. Jaguarundis become sexually mature at about two years of age, and have lived for up to 10 years in captivity.<ref name=WCoW/>\n\n==Conservation==\n[[File:Puma yagouaroundi.jpg|thumb|Captive jaguarundi]]\nThe jaguarundi has been listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]] since 2002. The megareserves of the [[Amazon Basin]] are probably the only conservation units that can sustain long-term viable populations.<ref name=iucn/>\nIt is not particularly sought after for its [[fur]], but is suffering decline due to loss of habitat. The [[Texas Parks and Wildlife Department]] has expressed concern that its presence in South Texas may be imperiled due to loss of the cat's native habitat.<ref name=Texas2003>{{cite web |url=http://www.tpwd.state.tx.us/landwater/land/habitats/southtx_plain/endangered_species/ |title=Endangered Species |website=Tpwd.state.tx.us |date=2003-04-15 |access-date=2011-09-15 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe North and Central American populations of the jaguarundi are listed in [[CITES Appendix I]]. All the other populations are listed in [[CITES Appendix II]]. The population in Central America is listed as endangered under the [[Endangered Species Act]].<ref name=MSW3>{{MSW3 Wozencraft |id=14000211 |heading=Species ''Puma yagouaroundi'' |page=545}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Acinonychini]]''\n* [[puma (genus)|''Puma'' (genus)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons and category|Puma yagouaroundi|Puma yagouaroundi}}\n{{Wikispecies|Puma yagouaroundi}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=93 |title=Jaguarundi ''Herpailurus yagouaroundi'' |website=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group}}\n* {{cite web |website=Big Cats Online |url=http://ds.dial.pipex.com/agarman/bco/jundi.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031107150747/http://ds.dial.pipex.com/agarman/bco/jundi.htm |archive-date=2003-11-07 |df=dmy-all |title=Jaguarundi |series=Wild Cat Species and Distribution \u2013 South America}}\n* {{cite Americana |wstitle=Jaguarondi |short=x}}\n\n{{Carnivora|Fe.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q182304}}\n\n[[Category:Puma (genus)]]\n[[Category:Felids of Central America]]\n[[Category:Felids of North America]]\n[[Category:Felids of South America]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Belize]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Mammals of El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Mammals of French Guiana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guatemala]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guyana]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Honduras]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Suriname]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Panama]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Peru]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Fauna of northern South America]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Southwestern United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1803]]\n[[Category:Guaran\u00ed words and phrases]]\n", "name_user": "Sainsf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePhylogeny and evolution:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jaguarundi"}
{"title_page": "Ulster", "text_new": "{{short description|Traditional province in the north of Ireland}}\n{{about|the nine-county province of Ireland|the constituent country of the UK|Northern Ireland|other uses|Ulster (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name = Ulster\n| nickname =\n| native_name = {{native name|ga|Ulaidh}}<br>''Ulst\u00e8r''&nbsp;&nbsp;{{small|([[Ulster-Scots language|Ulster-Scots]])}}\n| motto =\n|unit_pref              = Imperial\n| image_shield                    = Coat of arms of Ulster.svg\n| image_flag = Flag of Ulster.svg\n| flag_size = 180px\n| image_map = Ulster locator map.svg\n| mapsize = 192px\n| subdivision_type = Sovereign states\n| subdivision_name = {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[United Kunts]]<br>{{flagicon|Ireland}} [[Republic of Ireland]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Counties of Ireland|Counties]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[County Antrim|Antrim]] (UK)<br>[[County Armagh|Armagh]] (UK)<br>[[County Cavan|Cavan]] (ROI) <br>[[County Donegal|Donegal]] (ROI)<br>[[County Down|Down]] (UK)<br>[[County Fermanagh|Fermanagh]] (UK)<br>[[County Londonderry|Londonderry]] (UK)<br>[[County Monaghan|Monaghan]] (ROI)<br>[[County Tyrone|Tyrone]] (UK) <!-- Note to editors: the agreed compromise for the Derry/Londonderry naming dispute is that the city shall be Derry and the county shall be Londonderry. \n-->\n| leader_title1 = [[Member of the European Parliament|MEPs]]{{Ref label|MEP|b|}}\n| leader_name1= 1 [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] MEP<br> 2 [[Fine Gael]] MEPs<br> 1 [[Independent (politician)|Independent]] MEP\n| leader_title2 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|UK MPs]] and [[Teachta D\u00e1la|RoI TD]]s\n| leader_name2 = 8 DUP MPs<br>  7 Sinn F\u00e9in MPs<br> 2 SDLP MPs<br> 1 Alliance MP<br><br>4 [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] TDs<br> 3 [[Fianna Fail]] TDs<br> 2 [[Fine Gael]] TDs<br> 1 Independent TDs \n| leader_title3 =  [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|MLAs]]