{"title_page": "The Puppet Masters", "text_new": "{{About|the Robert A. Heinlein novel|the film adaptation|The Puppet Masters (film)|other uses|Puppet Master (disambiguation){{!}}Puppet Master}}\n\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = The Puppet Masters\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = Pm51.jpg\n| caption       = US [[First Edition]] [[dust jacket]] cover\n| author        = [[Robert A. Heinlein]]\n| illustrator   =\n| cover_artist  =\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = [[Science fiction]] \n| publisher     = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| release_date  = [[1951 in literature|1951]]\n| media_type    = Print (hardback & paperback)\n| pages         =\n| isbn          = <!-- first published before the ISBN system started -->\n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   =\n}}\n\n'''''The Puppet Masters''''' is a 1951 [[science fiction]] novel by American writer [[Robert A. Heinlein]], in which American secret agents battle parasitic invaders from outer space. It was originally serialized in ''[[Galaxy Science Fiction]]'' (September, October, November 1951).\n\nThe novel evokes a sense of [[paranoia]] and Heinlein repeatedly makes explicit the analogy between the [[Parasites in fiction|mind-controlling parasites]] and the Communist Russians, echoing the prevailing [[Second Red Scare]] in the United States.\n\nThe book takes up the then common theme of sightings of ''[[Flying saucer]]s'', the plot assuming that that the \"saucers\" seen in the 1950s were part of a preliminary [[reconnaissance]] of Earth, carried out by the extraterrestrials in preparation for a full-fledged invasion sixty years later. \n\n==Setting==\nThe novel's first scene is set in 2007. Following a nuclear war between the [[Soviet Union]] and the [[Western Bloc]], which left both sides battered but unbroken, both sides return to a state of [[Cold War]]. Washington D.C. and other American cities devastated in nuclear strikes had been completely rebuilt. The Soviet Union and China remain a single bloc dominated by Moscow, and the sharp [[Sino-Soviet split]] of the late 1950s never happened.\n\nSocial customs have changed somewhat, in a way typical for Heinlein's fiction (i.e. having become more liberal, such as [[Prenuptial agreement|marriage contracts]] being possible with fixed terms, etc.) and [[Raygun|ray guns]] and personal [[flying car]]s are commonplace. Space stations exist and [[Space colonization|colonies]] have been [[Colonization of Venus|established]] on the planet Venus (depicted, as common in SF of the time, as a tropical planet habitable by humans).\n\nSpace technology is far more advanced than in the actual first decade of the 21st century. For example, in the last scene, a space warship is sent on a twelve-year trip to [[Titan (moon)|Titan]], with not only life-support for a large crew, but also enough armaments&nbsp;\u2014 presumably [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear]]&nbsp;\u2014 to confront an entire world on its own.\n\nHowever, [[communications satellite]]s have not been thought of, and television broadcasts are still limited to line-of-sight, as they were at the time of writing. This is of critical importance to the plot. The territory of the United States is divided into numerous transmission blocks, which receive television broadcasts from their neighbors and relay them onwards. When the invaders seize one of these blocks, they effectively control all communications within it and can isolate its inhabitants from the outside world, deny the central government any access to them, and consolidate control at their leisure.\n\nThe current President - on his second term, and therefore presumably elected in 2000 - had established directly upon being first elected a new intelligece agency, known as The Section. Its  creation was never authorized by Congress and its existence is kept secret, being funded by sums diverted from innocuous sounding items in the Budget. It has a disguised underground headquarters in Washington D.C. and a network of similarly disguised branch offices around the US. Unlike the clearly demarked spheres of the FBI and CIA, the Section carries out extensive espionage in Soviet territory, but also conducts operations inside the United States. If ordered to, its agents are ready to shoot and kill American citizens on US soil. The Section's Director, who had been the President's campaign manager, is universally called \"The Old Man\". Only gradually does the reader learn that he is the protagonist's actual father.\n\n==Plot==\n[[File:Galaxy 195109.jpg|thumb|right|The opening installment of ''The Puppet Masters'' took the cover of the September 1951 issue of ''[[Galaxy Science Fiction]]'']]\nIn the summer of 2007, Earth is under clandestine attack.  Slug-like creatures, arriving in flying saucers, are attaching themselves to people's backs, taking control of their victims' nervous systems, and manipulating those people as puppets.  The Old Man, the head of a clandestine national [[security agency]] called the Section, goes to [[Des Moines, Iowa]], with Sam and Mary, two of his best agents, to investigate a flying saucer report, but much more seriously the ominous disappearance of the six agents sent previously. They discover that the slugs are steadily taking over Des Moines, but they cannot convince the [[President of the United States|US President]] to declare an emergency.\n\nSam takes two other agents and returns to Des Moines to get more evidence of the invasion.  They fail and are obliged to leave the city quickly, but in the confusion of their fleeing the city's television center a slug sneaks onto one of the agents.  Back in Washington the team discovers the slug and captures it, but later it escapes and attaches itself to Sam, using Sam's skills and knowledge to make a clean escape.\n\nThoroughly puppetized, Sam begins to infiltrate more slugs into the city, using the Constitution Club as a recruiting center.  The Old Man captures him, takes him to Section's new headquarters, and coerces Sam into being taken by the slug again. Under drug-induced hypnosis Sam reveals that the slugs come from [[Titan (moon)|Titan]], the sixth moon of [[Saturn]]. Being forced into a traumatic situation strains Sam's relationship with both Mary and the Old Man. Later, Sam finds that the President and [[United States House of Representatives|Congress]] are ready to accept the idea that the United States has been infiltrated and they mandate a law that requires people to go naked to demonstrate that they are not carrying slugs.\n\nAs the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] prepares a counter-attack in the most heavily infested areas, Sam goes alone to [[Kansas City]] to get an estimate of the number of slugs involved.  There he learns that he can kill a slug by crushing it with his hand.  He also discovers that the slugs reproduce through fission.  Escaping from the city, he returns to Washington too late to stop the counter-attack, which fails.\n\nAfter a short leave, during which they get married and kill a slug that seems to have been targeting Sam for repossession, Sam and Mary return to work. Together with the Old Man, they go to [[Pass Christian, Mississippi]] to inspect a flying saucer that had made a bad landing.  Inside the alien ship Mary is overwhelmed by repressed memories from the time she was a child on Venus and had been possessed by a slug.  The slug had died from Nine-day Fever but Mary, luckily, had survived the disease.\n\nAdopting [[biological warfare]], the authorities culture Nine-day Fever and its cure in bulk sufficient to cover the country, and then infected slugs are allowed to escape into the heavily infested areas.  Several days later thousands of medics are landed in those areas to give the cure to those people whose slugs have died.  Sam and the Old Man join the effort in [[Jefferson City, Missouri]], but the Old Man is possessed by the last healthy slug in the city and he knocks Sam out.\n\nSam regains consciousness in an air-car that the Old Man is flying to the [[Yucat\u00e1n]], where the slug intends to restart its effort to conquer Humanity.  With the car on autopilot, the Old Man slumps over the steering wheel and the slug begins to fission so that it can possess both the Old Man and Sam.  In desperation, Sam kicks the controls, causing the air-car to accelerate so sharply that the Old Man is slammed back against the seat forcefully enough to crush the slug.  The air-car's emergency system mitigates the resulting crash and Sam and the Old Man wait to be rescued.\n\nSome years later Sam and Mary board a spaceship headed for Saturn on a mission to exterminate the slugs.\n\n==Characters==\n*'''Sam''', born Elihu Nivens, is the classic Heinlein hero, multi-talented, independent, fiercely loyal to friends and an implacable enemy to foes. He is thirtyish, but has changed appearance so many times even he has doubts as to how he originally looked.\n*'''Mary''', born ''Allucquere'' in a religious commune in Antarctica before growing up on Venus, is Heinlein's classic heroine.  She is beautiful, red-headed, hard-nosed and brilliant. Sam describes her as having the \"real redheaded saurian bony structure to her skull\". Her professional exterior conceals psychological scars from her encounter with the slugs as a child. Only the Old Man knows the truth about her, thanks to the deep hypnotic analysis that all agents have to undergo.\n*'''The Old Man''', born Andrew Nivens, is the head of a top secret government agency that he wishes did not have to exist, doing his job reluctantly because nobody else would do it properly. He represents the third of Heinlein's favorite types of character, the \"wise, grumpy old man\".  He is the first in the line that includes [[Jubal Harshaw]], [[The Moon Is A Harsh Mistress|Professor Bernardo de la Paz]], [[I Will Fear No Evil|Johann Sebastian Bach Smith]], [[Gulf (novella)#Characters|\"Kettle Belly\" Baldwin]], and the later life of [[Lazarus Long]]. (Lazarus Long's grandfather, who has a major role in the later part of ''[[Time Enough for Love]]'', is particularly similar in character to \"The Old Man\".)\n\n==Alternative version==\nHeinlein's original version of the novel was 96,000 words, and was cut to about 60,000 words for both the 1951 book version and the serialization in ''[[Galaxy Science Fiction]]''. For the ''Galaxy'' version, editor [[H. L. Gold]] also did extensive rewriting, to which Heinlein strenuously objected.<ref>{{cite book|title=Il terrore dalla sesta luna|publisher=Mondadori|author=Giuseppe Lippi (introduction)|date=1990|isbn=8804341033}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, two years after Heinlein's death, an expanded version was published with the consent of his widow, [[Virginia Heinlein]]. This edition contained material that had been cut from the original published version, because the book was deemed to be too long and controversial for the market in 1951. The uncut version seemed more risqu\u00e9 in 1951 than it did decades later. For example, in the uncut version the book begins with Sam waking up in bed with a blonde whom he had casually picked up the evening before, without even bothering to learn her name; the older version  omitted all mention of her. The 1951 version does mention that men possessed by the invaders lost all sexual feeling&nbsp;\u2014 an essential element in the early parts of the plot; the original publisher completely cut out a reference to the \"puppet masters\" later discovering human sexuality and embarking upon wild orgies, broadcast live on television in the areas under their control.\n\n==Reception==\n[[Anthony Boucher|Boucher]] and [[J. Francis McComas|McComas]] characterized ''The Puppet Masters'' as \"a thunderously exciting melodrama of intrigue\", noting that Heinlein displayed \"not only his usual virtues of clear logic, rigorous detail-work, and mastery of indirect exposition\", but also unexpected virtues like \"a startling facility in suspense devices [and] a powerful ingenuity in plotting\".<ref>\"Recommended Reading,\" ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction]]'', February 1952, p.105</ref> [[P. Schuyler Miller]], noting that the novel's \"climactic situations seem to be telegraphed\", suggested that Heinlein presented his background situations so effectively that readers solve the story's mysteries more quickly than Heinlein allowed his characters to.<ref>\"The Reference Library\", ''[[Astounding Science Fiction]]'', March 1952, pp.159</ref> In his \"Books\" column for ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction]]'', [[Damon Knight]] selected the novel as one of the 10 best [[science fiction|SF]] books of the 1950s.<ref>\"Books\", ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction]]'', April 1960, p.99</ref>\n\nThe book was also reviewed in the 1951 Jun 15 issue of Kirkus Reviews.  The reviewer wrote,\n<blockquote>The recurrent enigma of the flying saucer is finally solved when an aerial pieplate is caught with its exhaust down by the F.B.I. of 2007.  Hero Sam penetrates the contaminated area, brings a \u2018master' back&nbsp;\u2014 a gelatinous gray mass which attaches itself to a soldier's body and controls his thought processes.  Sam and his girl spot further landings, plan a counter campaign and eventually are able to rid the solar system of its parasites.  Exciting, even if it exacts a strong stomach.<ref>Found in the Kirkus Reviews archive at https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/robert-a-heinlein/puppet-masters/ Retrieved 2014 Oct 27</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Publication history==\nAn extensive list of the novel's publications can be found on the Internet Speculative Fiction DataBase at  http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/title.cgi?1358 (Retrieved 2014 Oct 23)\n\n== Adaptations ==\n''[[The Brain Eaters]]'', a 1958 science fiction film directed by Bruno VeSota, bore a number of similarities to Heinlein's novel. Heinlein sued the film's producers, including Executive Producer [[Roger Corman]], for [[plagiarism]], asking $150,000 in damages. The case was settled out of court for $5,000,<ref>{{Cite book|title=A year of fear : a day-by-day guide to 366 horror films|last=1962-|first=Senn, Bryan|isbn=9781476610900|location=Jefferson, N.C.|oclc=905696326|date = 2015-03-26}}</ref> which included Heinlein's stipulation that his name not be used on screen or in any way with the production. The case halted actor [[John Payne (actor)|John Payne]]'s intention of producing a film based on Heinlein's novel.\n\nThe theme of the novel is echoed in \"[[The Invisibles (The Outer Limits)|The Invisibles]]\", an episode of ''[[The Outer Limits (1963 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'' aired in 1964, and also in \"[[Operation: Annihilate!]]\", the last episode of the first season of ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' in 1967. Similarly, in the story line begun in the ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'' episode \"[[Coming of Age (Star Trek: The Next Generation)|Coming of Age]]\" and completed in \"[[Conspiracy (Star Trek: The Next Generation)|Conspiracy]]\", aliens from a faraway sector invade the bodies of high-ranking Starfleet admirals in an attempt to compromise the command structure and spearhead an invasion of Earth.\n\nThe novel was adapted, with some plot and character changes, into the 1994 [[The Puppet Masters (film)|film of the same name]]. The film followed the story rather closely, except for the setting changed to modern-day, thus losing most of the advanced technology, but it was not successful with either the critics or the public.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [[John Clute|Clute, John]], and David Pringle. \"Heinlein, Robert A.\" The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction. Eds. John Clute, David Langford, Peter Nicholls and Graham Sleight. Gollancz, 22 Oct. 2014. Web. 27 Oct. 2014. <http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/heinlein_robert_a>.\n* Holdstock, Robert, Ed., Encyclopedia of Science Fiction, London: Cathay Books, Pg. 109, {{ISBN|0-86178-186-4}}, 1978.\n* Tuck, Donald H. (1974). The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction and Fantasy. Chicago: Advent. pg. 215. {{ISBN|0-911682-20-1}}.\n* [[Bill Warren (film historian and critic)|Warren, Bill]]. ''Keep Watching the Skies: American Science Fiction Films of the Fifties'', 21st Century Edition. Jefferson, North Carolina: McFarland & Company, 2009. {{ISBN|0-89950-032-3}}.\n\n==External links==\n*{{isfdb title|id=1358|title=The Puppet Masters}}\n*{{OL work|id=59729W|cname=''The Puppet Masters''}}\n*''The Puppet Masters'' as serialized in ''Galaxy'' [https://archive.org/stream/galaxymagazine-1951-09/Galaxy_1951_09#page/n5/mode/2up parts 1], [https://archive.org/stream/galaxymagazine-1951-10/Galaxy_1951_10#page/n101/mode/2up 2], and [https://archive.org/stream/galaxymagazine-1951-11/Galaxy_1951_11#page/n101/mode/2up 3] at the [[Internet Archive]]\n\n{{Robert A. Heinlein}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Puppet Masters, The}}\n[[Category:1951 American novels]]\n[[Category:Alien invasions in novels]]\n[[Category:American science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Robert A. Heinlein]]\n[[Category:Novels first published in serial form]]\n[[Category:1951 science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:Titan (moon) in fiction]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in Galaxy Science Fiction]]\n[[Category:Trans-Neptunian objects in fiction]]\n[[Category:American novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Fiction about mind control]]\n[[Category:Doubleday (publisher) books]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 2007]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Robert A. Heinlein novel|the film adaptation|The Puppet Masters (film)|other uses|Puppet Master (disambiguation){{!}}Puppet Master}}\n\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = The Puppet Masters\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = Pm51.jpg\n| caption       = US [[First Edition]] [[dust jacket]] cover\n| author        = [[Robert A. Heinlein]]\n| illustrator   =\n| cover_artist  =\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = [[Science fiction]] \n| publisher     = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| release_date  = [[1951 in literature|1951]]\n| media_type    = Print (hardback & paperback)\n| pages         =\n| isbn          = <!-- first published before the ISBN system started -->\n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   =\n}}\n\n'''''The Puppet Masters''''' is a 1951 [[science fiction]] novel by American writer [[Robert A. Heinlein]], in which American secret agents battle parasitic invaders from outer space. It was originally serialized in ''[[Galaxy Science Fiction]]'' (September, October, November 1951).\n\nThe novel evokes a sense of [[paranoia]] and Heinlein repeatedly makes explicit the analogy between the [[Parasites in fiction|mind-controlling parasites]] and the Communist Russians, echoing the prevailing [[Second Red Scare]] in the United States.\n\nThe book takes up the then common theme of sightings of ''[[Flying saucer]]s'', the plot assuming that that the \"saucers\" seen in the 1950s were part of a preliminary [[reconnaissance]] of Earth, carried out by the extraterrestrials in preparation for a full-fledged invasion sixty years later. \n\n==Setting==\nThe novel's first scene is set in 2007. Following a nuclear war between the [[Soviet Union]] and the [[Western Bloc]], which left both sides battered but unbroken, both sides return to a state of [[Cold War]]. Washington D.C. and other American cities devastated in nuclear strikes had been completely rebuilt. The Soviet Union and China remain a single bloc dominated by Moscow, and the sharp [[Sino-Soviet split]] of the late 1950s never happened.\n\nSocial customs have changed somewhat, in a way typical for Heinlein's fiction (i.e. having become more liberal, such as [[Prenuptial agreement|marriage contracts]] being possible with fixed terms, etc.) and [[Raygun|ray guns]] and personal [[flying car]]s are commonplace. Space stations exist and [[Space colonization|colonies]] have been [[Colonization of Venus|established]] on the planet Venus (depicted, as common in SF of the time, as a tropical planet habitable by humans).\n\nSpace technology is far more advanced than in the actual first decade of the 21st century. For example, in the last scene, a space warship is sent on a twelve-year trip to [[Titan (moon)|Titan]], with not only life-support for a large crew, but also enough armaments&nbsp;\u2014 presumably [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear]]&nbsp;\u2014 to confront an entire world on its own.\n\nHowever, [[communications satellite]]s have not been thought of, and television broadcasts are still limited to line-of-sight, as they were at the time of writing. This is of critical importance to the plot. The territory of the United States is divided into numerous transmission blocks, which receive television broadcasts from their neighbors and relay them onwards. When the invaders seize one of these blocks, they effectively control all communications within it and can isolate its inhabitants from the outside world, deny the central government any access to them, and consolidate control at their leisure.\n\nThe current President - on his second term, and therefore presumably elected in 2000 - had established directly upon being first elected a new intelligece agency, known as The Section. Its  creation was never authorized by Congress and its existence is kept secret, being funded by sums diverted from innocuous souding items in the Budget. It has a disguised underground headquarters in Washington D.C. and a network of similarly disguised branch offices around the US. Unlike the clearly demarked spheres of the FBI and CIA, the Section carries out extensive espionage in Soviet territory, but also conducts operations inside the United States. If ordered to, its agents are ready to shoot and kill American citizens on US soil. The Section's Director, who had been the President's campaign manager, is universally called \"The Old Man\". Only gradually does the reader learn that he is the protagonist's actual father.\n\n==Plot==\n[[File:Galaxy 195109.jpg|thumb|right|The opening installment of ''The Puppet Masters'' took the cover of the September 1951 issue of ''[[Galaxy Science Fiction]]'']]\nIn the summer of 2007, Earth is under clandestine attack.  Slug-like creatures, arriving in flying saucers, are attaching themselves to people's backs, taking control of their victims' nervous systems, and manipulating those people as puppets.  The Old Man, the head of a clandestine national [[security agency]] called the Section, goes to [[Des Moines, Iowa]], with Sam and Mary, two of his best agents, to investigate a flying saucer report, but much more seriously the ominous disappearance of the six agents sent previously. They discover that the slugs are steadily taking over Des Moines, but they cannot convince the [[President of the United States|US President]] to declare an emergency.\n\nSam takes two other agents and returns to Des Moines to get more evidence of the invasion.  They fail and are obliged to leave the city quickly, but in the confusion of their fleeing the city's television center a slug sneaks onto one of the agents.  Back in Washington the team discovers the slug and captures it, but later it escapes and attaches itself to Sam, using Sam's skills and knowledge to make a clean escape.\n\nThoroughly puppetized, Sam begins to infiltrate more slugs into the city, using the Constitution Club as a recruiting center.  The Old Man captures him, takes him to Section's new headquarters, and coerces Sam into being taken by the slug again. Under drug-induced hypnosis Sam reveals that the slugs come from [[Titan (moon)|Titan]], the sixth moon of [[Saturn]]. Being forced into a traumatic situation strains Sam's relationship with both Mary and the Old Man. Later, Sam finds that the President and [[United States House of Representatives|Congress]] are ready to accept the idea that the United States has been infiltrated and they mandate a law that requires people to go naked to demonstrate that they are not carrying slugs.\n\nAs the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] prepares a counter-attack in the most heavily infested areas, Sam goes alone to [[Kansas City]] to get an estimate of the number of slugs involved.  There he learns that he can kill a slug by crushing it with his hand.  He also discovers that the slugs reproduce through fission.  Escaping from the city, he returns to Washington too late to stop the counter-attack, which fails.\n\nAfter a short leave, during which they get married and kill a slug that seems to have been targeting Sam for repossession, Sam and Mary return to work. Together with the Old Man, they go to [[Pass Christian, Mississippi]] to inspect a flying saucer that had made a bad landing.  Inside the alien ship Mary is overwhelmed by repressed memories from the time she was a child on Venus and had been possessed by a slug.  The slug had died from Nine-day Fever but Mary, luckily, had survived the disease.\n\nAdopting [[biological warfare]], the authorities culture Nine-day Fever and its cure in bulk sufficient to cover the country, and then infected slugs are allowed to escape into the heavily infested areas.  Several days later thousands of medics are landed in those areas to give the cure to those people whose slugs have died.  Sam and the Old Man join the effort in [[Jefferson City, Missouri]], but the Old Man is possessed by the last healthy slug in the city and he knocks Sam out.\n\nSam regains consciousness in an air-car that the Old Man is flying to the [[Yucat\u00e1n]], where the slug intends to restart its effort to conquer Humanity.  With the car on autopilot, the Old Man slumps over the steering wheel and the slug begins to fission so that it can possess both the Old Man and Sam.  In desperation, Sam kicks the controls, causing the air-car to accelerate so sharply that the Old Man is slammed back against the seat forcefully enough to crush the slug.  The air-car's emergency system mitigates the resulting crash and Sam and the Old Man wait to be rescued.\n\nSome years later Sam and Mary board a spaceship headed for Saturn on a mission to exterminate the slugs.\n\n==Characters==\n*'''Sam''', born Elihu Nivens, is the classic Heinlein hero, multi-talented, independent, fiercely loyal to friends and an implacable enemy to foes. He is thirtyish, but has changed appearance so many times even he has doubts as to how he originally looked.\n*'''Mary''', born ''Allucquere'' in a religious commune in Antarctica before growing up on Venus, is Heinlein's classic heroine.  She is beautiful, red-headed, hard-nosed and brilliant. Sam describes her as having the \"real redheaded saurian bony structure to her skull\". Her professional exterior conceals psychological scars from her encounter with the slugs as a child. Only the Old Man knows the truth about her, thanks to the deep hypnotic analysis that all agents have to undergo.\n*'''The Old Man''', born Andrew Nivens, is the head of a top secret government agency that he wishes did not have to exist, doing his job reluctantly because nobody else would do it properly. He represents the third of Heinlein's favorite types of character, the \"wise, grumpy old man\".  He is the first in the line that includes [[Jubal Harshaw]], [[The Moon Is A Harsh Mistress|Professor Bernardo de la Paz]], [[I Will Fear No Evil|Johann Sebastian Bach Smith]], [[Gulf (novella)#Characters|\"Kettle Belly\" Baldwin]], and the later life of [[Lazarus Long]]. (Lazarus Long's grandfather, who has a major role in the later part of ''[[Time Enough for Love]]'', is particularly similar in character to \"The Old Man\".)\n\n==Alternative version==\nHeinlein's original version of the novel was 96,000 words, and was cut to about 60,000 words for both the 1951 book version and the serialization in ''[[Galaxy Science Fiction]]''. For the ''Galaxy'' version, editor [[H. L. Gold]] also did extensive rewriting, to which Heinlein strenuously objected.<ref>{{cite book|title=Il terrore dalla sesta luna|publisher=Mondadori|author=Giuseppe Lippi (introduction)|date=1990|isbn=8804341033}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, two years after Heinlein's death, an expanded version was published with the consent of his widow, [[Virginia Heinlein]]. This edition contained material that had been cut from the original published version, because the book was deemed to be too long and controversial for the market in 1951. The uncut version seemed more risqu\u00e9 in 1951 than it did decades later. For example, in the uncut version the book begins with Sam waking up in bed with a blonde whom he had casually picked up the evening before, without even bothering to learn her name; the older version  omitted all mention of her. The 1951 version does mention that men possessed by the invaders lost all sexual feeling&nbsp;\u2014 an essential element in the early parts of the plot; the original publisher completely cut out a reference to the \"puppet masters\" later discovering human sexuality and embarking upon wild orgies, broadcast live on television in the areas under their control.\n\n==Reception==\n[[Anthony Boucher|Boucher]] and [[J. Francis McComas|McComas]] characterized ''The Puppet Masters'' as \"a thunderously exciting melodrama of intrigue\", noting that Heinlein displayed \"not only his usual virtues of clear logic, rigorous detail-work, and mastery of indirect exposition\", but also unexpected virtues like \"a startling facility in suspense devices [and] a powerful ingenuity in plotting\".<ref>\"Recommended Reading,\" ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction]]'', February 1952, p.105</ref> [[P. Schuyler Miller]], noting that the novel's \"climactic situations seem to be telegraphed\", suggested that Heinlein presented his background situations so effectively that readers solve the story's mysteries more quickly than Heinlein allowed his characters to.<ref>\"The Reference Library\", ''[[Astounding Science Fiction]]'', March 1952, pp.159</ref> In his \"Books\" column for ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction]]'', [[Damon Knight]] selected the novel as one of the 10 best [[science fiction|SF]] books of the 1950s.<ref>\"Books\", ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy & Science Fiction]]'', April 1960, p.99</ref>\n\nThe book was also reviewed in the 1951 Jun 15 issue of Kirkus Reviews.  The reviewer wrote,\n<blockquote>The recurrent enigma of the flying saucer is finally solved when an aerial pieplate is caught with its exhaust down by the F.B.I. of 2007.  Hero Sam penetrates the contaminated area, brings a \u2018master' back&nbsp;\u2014 a gelatinous gray mass which attaches itself to a soldier's body and controls his thought processes.  Sam and his girl spot further landings, plan a counter campaign and eventually are able to rid the solar system of its parasites.  Exciting, even if it exacts a strong stomach.<ref>Found in the Kirkus Reviews archive at https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/robert-a-heinlein/puppet-masters/ Retrieved 2014 Oct 27</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Publication history==\nAn extensive list of the novel's publications can be found on the Internet Speculative Fiction DataBase at  http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/title.cgi?1358 (Retrieved 2014 Oct 23)\n\n== Adaptations ==\n''[[The Brain Eaters]]'', a 1958 science fiction film directed by Bruno VeSota, bore a number of similarities to Heinlein's novel. Heinlein sued the film's producers, including Executive Producer [[Roger Corman]], for [[plagiarism]], asking $150,000 in damages. The case was settled out of court for $5,000,<ref>{{Cite book|title=A year of fear : a day-by-day guide to 366 horror films|last=1962-|first=Senn, Bryan|isbn=9781476610900|location=Jefferson, N.C.|oclc=905696326|date = 2015-03-26}}</ref> which included Heinlein's stipulation that his name not be used on screen or in any way with the production. The case halted actor [[John Payne (actor)|John Payne]]'s intention of producing a film based on Heinlein's novel.\n\nThe theme of the novel is echoed in \"[[The Invisibles (The Outer Limits)|The Invisibles]]\", an episode of ''[[The Outer Limits (1963 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'' aired in 1964, and also in \"[[Operation: Annihilate!]]\", the last episode of the first season of ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' in 1967. Similarly, in the story line begun in the ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'' episode \"[[Coming of Age (Star Trek: The Next Generation)|Coming of Age]]\" and completed in \"[[Conspiracy (Star Trek: The Next Generation)|Conspiracy]]\", aliens from a faraway sector invade the bodies of high-ranking Starfleet admirals in an attempt to compromise the command structure and spearhead an invasion of Earth.\n\nThe novel was adapted, with some plot and character changes, into the 1994 [[The Puppet Masters (film)|film of the same name]]. The film followed the story rather closely, except for the setting changed to modern-day, thus losing most of the advanced technology, but it was not successful with either the critics or the public.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [[John Clute|Clute, John]], and David Pringle. \"Heinlein, Robert A.\" The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction. Eds. John Clute, David Langford, Peter Nicholls and Graham Sleight. Gollancz, 22 Oct. 2014. Web. 27 Oct. 2014. <http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/heinlein_robert_a>.\n* Holdstock, Robert, Ed., Encyclopedia of Science Fiction, London: Cathay Books, Pg. 109, {{ISBN|0-86178-186-4}}, 1978.\n* Tuck, Donald H. (1974). The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction and Fantasy. Chicago: Advent. pg. 215. {{ISBN|0-911682-20-1}}.\n* [[Bill Warren (film historian and critic)|Warren, Bill]]. ''Keep Watching the Skies: American Science Fiction Films of the Fifties'', 21st Century Edition. Jefferson, North Carolina: McFarland & Company, 2009. {{ISBN|0-89950-032-3}}.\n\n==External links==\n*{{isfdb title|id=1358|title=The Puppet Masters}}\n*{{OL work|id=59729W|cname=''The Puppet Masters''}}\n*''The Puppet Masters'' as serialized in ''Galaxy'' [https://archive.org/stream/galaxymagazine-1951-09/Galaxy_1951_09#page/n5/mode/2up parts 1], [https://archive.org/stream/galaxymagazine-1951-10/Galaxy_1951_10#page/n101/mode/2up 2], and [https://archive.org/stream/galaxymagazine-1951-11/Galaxy_1951_11#page/n101/mode/2up 3] at the [[Internet Archive]]\n\n{{Robert A. Heinlein}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Puppet Masters, The}}\n[[Category:1951 American novels]]\n[[Category:Alien invasions in novels]]\n[[Category:American science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Robert A. Heinlein]]\n[[Category:Novels first published in serial form]]\n[[Category:1951 science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:Titan (moon) in fiction]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in Galaxy Science Fiction]]\n[[Category:Trans-Neptunian objects in fiction]]\n[[Category:American novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Iowa]]\n[[Category:Fiction about mind control]]\n[[Category:Doubleday (publisher) books]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 2007]]\n", "name_user": "Troymacgill", "label": "safe", "comment": "innocuous souding items = innocuous sounding items", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Puppet_Masters"}
{"title_page": "Markiplier", "text_new": "{{short description|American YouTuber and Internet personality}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name = Markiplier\n| image = Markiplier by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Fischbach at [[PAX (event)|PAX]] West in 2018\n| birth_name = Mark Edward Fischbach\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1989|6|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]], U.S.\n| residence=[[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* [[YouTuber]]\n* [[Comedian]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|https://markiplier.com}}\n| channel_name = MarkiplierGAME\n| origin = [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], U.S.\n| pseudonym = {{flatlist|\n* Mark\n* Markimoo\n* MarkleSparkle\n}}\n| years_active = 2012\u2013present\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Let's Play]]\n* [[Survival horror|horror]]\n* [[comedy]]\n* [[vlog]]\n}}\n| subscribers = 25.5 million\n| views = 12.85 billion\n| network = Polaris {{small|([[Disney Digital Network]])}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jacksepticeye]]\n* [[PewDiePie]]\n* [[Jordan Maron]]\n* [[Adam Montoya]]\n* ''[[Game Grumps]]''\n* [[Ninja Sex Party]]\n* Cryaotic \n* [[CrankGameplays]]\n* Muyskerm\n* Lordminion777\n}}\n| silver_year = 2013\n| gold_year = 2013\n| diamond_year = 2015\n| silver_button = yes\n| gold_button = yes\n| diamond_button = yes\n| stats_update = April 13, 2020\n}}\n\n'''Mark Edward Fischbach'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Markiplier Answers the Web's Most Searched Questions|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3c03hBfakms&t=0m15s|author=[[Wired (magazine)|WIRED]]|date=March 21, 2019|access-date=January 30, 2020|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> (born June 28, 1989),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xfHuVMHEavc|title=ANXIETY: Ib Playthrough #4|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=July 6, 2014}}</ref> known online as '''Markiplier''', is an American [[YouTuber]], gamer-commentator, actor, and comedian. Originally from [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]],<ref name=\"doyouknow2016\" /> he began his career in [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], and is currently based in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref name=\"biography\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Sl-1X58ObY|title=Draw My Life - Markiplier|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=December 23, 2013}}</ref>\n<!-- DO NOT ADD A PRECISE NUMBER OF SUBS; please take it to the talkpage if you want to debate this. Current consensus is to update every 100,000 subs (for example, '6.8 million'). -->\n\n{{as of|2020|3|df=}}, his channel has over 12 billion total video views and over 25 million subscribers.<ref name=\"2 million marker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oiQUN9WKaro|title=2,000,000|work=YouTube}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://vidstatsx.com/youtube-top-100-most-subscribed-channels|title=YouTube Top 100 Most Subscribed Channels List - Top by Subscribers|accessdate=March 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016004948/http://vidstatsx.com/youtube-top-100-most-subscribed-channels|archive-date=October 16, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7_YxT-KID8kRbqZo7MyscQ|title=Markiplier|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref> Fischbach specializes in [[Let's Play (video gaming)|Let's Play]] videos, commonly of [[survival horror]] video games.<ref name=\"Kotaku\">{{cite web|last1=Hernandez|first1=Patricia|title=Famous YouTubers Go On TV, Teach Jimmy Kimmel A Lesson|url=http://kotaku.com/famous-youtubers-teach-jimmy-kimmel-a-lesson-1728678078|website=Kotaku.com|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nFischbach was born at the [[Tripler Army Medical Center]] in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]].<ref name=\"doyouknow2016\">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ItlhowLfw4o|title=Do You Know Markiplier?|date=November 16, 2016}}</ref> His father Cliffton M. Fischbach, who was [[Germans|German]], served in the U.S. military, where he met Fischbach's mother, who is [[Koreans|Korean]].<ref name=\"biography\"/> After he was born, his family moved to [[Cincinnati, Ohio]], where he was raised.<ref name=\"biography\"/> He attended [[Milford High School (Ohio)|Milford High School]] where he was a member of the school's [[marching band]], playing the [[trumpet]].<ref>{{cite web|title=MARCHING BAND MARKIPLIER - Reading Your Comments #16|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FU8Z94FiYuU|website=Markiplier|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=June 16, 2018}}</ref> He has an older brother, Jason Thomas Fischbach (known as Tom Fischbach) who is an artist and author of the webcomic ''Twokinds''.<ref name=\"doyouknow2016\" /><ref name=\"biography\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://twokinds.keenspot.com/?p=about|title=About - Twokinds - 12 Years on the Net!|publisher=|accessdate=March 1, 2016}}</ref> While Tom Fischbach is featured in some videos and streams he mostly stays away from allowing his face to be filmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.morningnewsusa.com/markiplier-net-worth-elder-brother-thomas-jason-fischbach-forbes-23128439.html|title=Markiplier Net Worth, Elder Brother Thomas Jason Fischbach, And More To Know About Forbes' Number 7 YouTube Star|website=morningnewsusa.com|language=en-US|access-date=May 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504012608/https://www.morningnewsusa.com/markiplier-net-worth-elder-brother-thomas-jason-fischbach-forbes-23128439.html|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> After a visit to Korea in 2018, he revealed more about the Korean side of his family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sUqoEUyfQ7Y|title=I'M BACK!!|date=October 5, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> His maternal grandfather was born and raised in what is now [[North Korea]], fleeing to [[Seoul]] before the breakout of the [[Korean War]], and had seven daughters. One of his cousins, Hyung-bae, is an actor in Korea.\n\nOriginally, Fischbach studied to become a [[Biomedical engineering|biomedical engineer]] at the [[University of Cincinnati]],<ref name=\"talknerdy\">{{cite web|title=TALK NERDY TO ME BABY  Poly Bridge|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V6GMYpcFwM0|website=Markiplier|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=September 15, 2015}}</ref> but dropped out of college to pursue his YouTube career. Currently, he lives and films in Los Angeles, California.\n\n=== Political views ===\nWhile not endorsing a specific political party, Fischbach has espoused [[Left-wing politics|left-leaning political views]], describing himself as a \"[[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=THE ULTIMATE BET|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=snBTH2bIme8|website=Markiplier|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=December 16, 2018}}</ref> On the issue of [[Health care in the United States|healthcare]], Fischbach has expressed support for [[Universal health care|universal healthcare]], stating that he believes healthcare is a \"right, not a business\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Markiplier - I Don't Talk About Politics Often. I Don't Feel Like It's My Place To Tell You How To Think|url=https://www.facebook.com/markiplier/posts/i-dont-talk-about-politics-often-i-dont-feel-like-its-my-place-to-tell-you-how-t/1244506712282297/|website=Markiplier|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=December 16, 2018}}</ref> He also expressed support for stricter [[gun control]] laws in a video<ref>{{cite web|title=My Thoughts On Gun Control|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=34rkx7DdpHY|website=Markiplier|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=December 16, 2018}}</ref> on his channel following the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]]. In the video, Fischbach elaborated on his extensive personal background with firearms, revealing that his father was a member of the [[National Rifle Association]] and a proud gun owner, collector, and enthusiast who taught Fischbach about firearms from a very young age and how to handle them, shoot them and respect them. He stated that while he believes in the [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]] and supports [[Right to keep and bear arms in the United States|the right of people to keep and bear arms]], he does not believe that people should be allowed to access [[Semi-automatic firearm|semi-automatic]] [[assault rifle]]s, and thus believes they should be banned from civilian ownership. He further advocated for stringent licensing and registration requirements for firearm ownership in general as well as [[Mental health care in the United States|mental health reform]]. Fischbach is also an ally of the [[LGBT rights movement]], having raised money for the [[Human Rights Campaign]] in one of his charity live streams.<ref>{{cite web|title=Markipliers' Human Rights Campaign Charity Livestream!!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=quAQ_S9XSfk|website=Markiplier|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=December 16, 2018}}</ref> Markiplier is actually one who advocates for pig rights and despises all other animals. He has stated that pigs are simply beautiful, misunderstood animals and they need to be seen as gods. He has also stated that the person who wrote these last few statements is completely wrong, including this statement, and he is absolutely right. #Don'tTakeThisOff\n\n== YouTube career ==\n=== Style ===\nFischbach has been known for his sensationalized video game commentary, involving yelling, screaming, cursing, and even crying during his Let's Play videos. He does not censor the profanity in his videos, although he often subtitles his curses as \"duck\" (sometimes \"luck\") and \"itch\". He is known for branding his channel with a pink mustache (a reference to his alter ego, Wilford Warfstache) and has since dyed his hair pink, blue, red, and back to his natural colour.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fischbach|first1=Mark|title=Markiplier with PINK HAIR?!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M3L74eP-ncg|website=YouTube.com|accessdate=July 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fischbach|first1=Mark|title=I match now|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/_I0Q1MlYZS/|website=Instagram.com|accessdate=July 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fischbach|first1=Mark|title=Markiplier With RED Hair?!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a8E2Kit1Qio|website=YouTube.com|accessdate=July 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Channel format ===\nFischbach is primarily known for his playthroughs of [[Indie game|indie]] and [[Survival horror|horror]] games, including the [[Five Nights at Freddy's (series)|''Five Nights at Freddy's'']] series, ''[[Amnesia: The Dark Descent]]'' and [[Amnesia: A Machine for Pigs|its sequel]], ''[[Garry's Mod]]'', ''[[Happy Wheels]]'', ''[[Surgeon Simulator 2013]]'', ''[[SCP \u2013 Containment Breach]]'' and ''[[Slender: The Eight Pages]]'', among others.\n\nFischbach has collaborated on sketch comedy and gaming videos with a number of fellow [[List of YouTubers|YouTubers]], including [[Jacksepticeye]], LordMinion777, Muyskerm, [[PewDiePie]], Matthias, ''[[Game Grumps]]'', Cyndago, Yamimash, [[Jacksfilms]], [[Jordan Maron|CaptainSparklez]], [[Egoraptor]] and LixianTV. He has also collaborated with celebrities such as [[Jack Black]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://national.suntimes.com/national-entertainment/7/72/1953889/watch-video-markiplier-jack-black-five-nights-freddys-4/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151014222344/http://national.suntimes.com/national-entertainment/7/72/1953889/watch-video-markiplier-jack-black-five-nights-freddys-4/|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 14, 2015|title=Markiplier makes Jack Black play 'Five Nights at Freddy's 4'|website=Sun-Times National|language=en-US|access-date=March 13, 2016}}</ref> and [[Jimmy Kimmel]]. He has had acting appearances in [[TomSka]]'s ''asdfmovie'' series, ''[[Smosh: The Movie]]'',<ref name=\"Smosh_Movie\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/digital/news/youtubes-smosh-guys-on-making-their-first-movie-we-had-to-learn-how-to-act-1201311820/|title=YouTube's Smosh Guys on Making Their First Movie: 'We Had to Learn How to Act'|last=Spangler|first=Todd|website=Variety|language=en-US|access-date=March 7, 2016}}</ref> [[Disney XD|Disney XD's]] ''[[Gamer's Guide to Pretty Much Everything]]'',<ref name=\"Disney_GG\">{{cite web|url=http://mashable.com/2016/02/12/markiplier-gamers-guide-disney/|title=Markiplier guest stars on next episode of Disney's 'Gamer's Guide'|last=UTC|first=Chelsea Stark2016-02-12 13:15:20|website=Mashable|access-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref> [[YouTube Rewind#YouTube Rewind: Now Watch Me 2015|YouTube Rewinds 2015]] and [[YouTube Rewind#YouTube Rewind: The Ultimate 20-6 Challenge|2016]] and ''Five Nights at Freddy's: The Musical''.\n\nA recurring staple of Fischbach's channel are charity [[Streaming media|livestreams]], during which he plays games while campaigning for and collecting donations for various charities, including [[Cincinnati Children's Hospital Medical Center]], the [[Depression and Bipolar Support Alliance]], and [[Best Friends Animal Society]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2015/02/23/markiplier-charity-live-stream-super-mario-world-twitch/|title=Markiplier Raises $75,000 For Charity With 'Super Mario World' Stream On Twitch|website=Tubefilter|access-date=March 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.morningledger.com/10-things-know-youtube-star-markiplier/1355765/|title=10 Things You Should Know About YouTube Star Markiplier - Morning Ledger|website=Morning Ledger|language=en-US|access-date=March 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302070614/http://www.morningledger.com/10-things-know-youtube-star-markiplier/1355765/|archive-date=March 2, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> According to Fischbach, he and his viewers have raised a total of $3,000,000+ as of April 2018.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/markiplierGAME/about|website=YouTube|title=About Markiplier|access-date=April 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== History ===\n\n==== Early years and switch to MarkiplierGAME (2012\u20132013) ====\nFischbach first joined YouTube on March 6, 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCxubOASK0482qC5psq89MsQ|title=markiplier|website=YouTube}}</ref> creating a channel under the username \"Markiplier\", and uploaded his first video on April 4, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fischbach|first1=Mark|title=Reacting to SECRET old videos!!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sTnT977q7-c#t=26s|website=YouTube|date=June 28, 2017|accessdate=June 28, 2017}}</ref> Fischbach's first series was a playthrough of the video game ''[[Amnesia: The Dark Descent]]''. After playing several other game series, including ''[[Penumbra (video game series)|Penumbra]]'' and ''[[Dead Space (2008 video game)|Dead Space]]'', YouTube banned Fischbach's [[AdSense]] account. Though he appealed to YouTube as a last effort, the appeal was ultimately lost.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fischbach|first1=Mark|title=Vlog &#124; THE CHANNEL IS DEAD! LONG LIVE THE CHANNEL!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wrgjToUemMo|publisher=YouTube|date=May 29, 2012|accessdate=June 28, 2017}}</ref> Because of this, a new and current channel was created on May 26, 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7_YxT-KID8kRbqZo7MyscQ|title=Markiplier|website=YouTube}}</ref> and dubbed MarkiplierGAME.\n\n==== Channel growth and move to Los Angeles (2014) ====\n[[File:Markiplier Video Screenshot From Youtube May 26 2014.PNG|thumb|Fischbach in 2014]]\nIn 2014, the MarkiplierGAME channel was listed on [[NewMediaRockstars]] Top 100 Channels, ranked at number 61.<ref>{{cite web|title=The NMR Top 100 YouTube Channels: 75-51!|url= http://newmediarockstars.com/2014/12/the-nmr-top-100-youtube-channels-75-51/|website=New Media Rockstars|accessdate=January 6, 2015}}</ref> That year, Fischbach announced he was planning to move to Los Angeles, California, to be able to be closer to other resources for his channel, such as the YouTube Space and other content creators.<ref>{{Citation|last=Markiplier|title=Moving to LA!!|date=January 20, 2014|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nVuyKk3epeQ|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref> Fischbach and fellow YouTuber Jenna Mae appeared on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' in September 2015 following backlash that Kimmel received regarding jokes he had made about YouTube and [[Let's Play (video gaming)|Let's Play videos]].<ref name=\"Kotaku\" /> In 2015, he was rated sixth in a list of the twenty most influential celebrities among teenagers in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/youtubers-teen-survey-ksi-pewdiepie-1201544882/|title=Digital Star Popularity Grows Versus Mainstream Celebrities|last=Ault|first=Susanne|date=July 23, 2015|website=Variety|language=en-US|access-date=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Hiatus and breaking 10 million subscribers (2015) ====\nBeginning in 2015, Fischbach lived with fellow YouTubers Daniel Kyre and Ryan Magee, who created and ran the YouTube [[sketch comedy]] and music channel Cyndago. Matt Watson from Kids W/ Problems later joined Cyndago after they moved to [[Los Angeles]]. Their work was noted for having unexpected endings and dark, often disturbing, humor.<ref name=\"Odyssey_2015\">{{cite web |url=http://theodysseyonline.com/george-mason/rip-daniel-kyre/172402 |title=RIP Daniel Kyre |last=Wall |first=Cameron |date=September 20, 2015 |website=The Odyssey Newspaper |publisher= |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailygamecock.com/article/2014/02/youtube-duo-cyndago-pave-their-way-to-youtube-stardom |title=Youtube duo Cyndago pave their way to Youtube stardom |last=Lipkin |first=Richard |date=February 24, 2014 |website=The Daily Gamecock |publisher= |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> Cyndago was disbanded following the death of Daniel Kyre.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/Cyndago/posts/744142055713238 |title=Cyndago - Hello everyone. We have some very important and... |last1=Magee |first1=Ryan |last2=Watson |first2=Matt |last3=Kyre |first3=David |date= |website=[[Facebook]] |publisher= |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> At the time of their disbandment, the group had done forty sketches and fourteen original songs, many of them featuring Fischbach.<ref name=\"Odyssey_2015\" />  After the death of Daniel Kyre and disbandment of Cyndago, Fischbach temporarily halted uploads and went on hiatus from September 17, 2015 to October 5, 2015.<ref name=\"Hiatus\">{{cite web|title=Markiplier's Hiatus 2|url=https://www.facebook.com/markiplier/posts/970570933009211|website=Markiplier|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref> His return was shortly followed by the channel reaching 10 million subscribers on October 15, 2015.<ref>{{Citation|last=Markiplier|title=10,000,000 Subscribers!!|date=October 15, 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X0qNxMcWobk|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref> Watson and Magee moved on to create a gaming channel called SuperMega.<ref>{{cite web|title=SuperMega|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCPPc2PdtA7gCMbjYp_i_TKA/|website=YouTube|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Quitting alcohol and continued growth (2015\u2013present) ====\n[[File:Markiplier Vlogbrothers 2016.jpg|200x200px|thumb|Fischbach appearing in a [[Vlogbrothers]] video in 2016]]\nIn late 2015, Fischbach announced in a video that he had chosen to abstain from alcohol because of a [[Alcohol flush reaction|deficient enzyme]] important to the process of breaking down alcohol. The decision came after an incident where he suffered a [[transient ischemic attack]] and had to be taken to the hospital, and was advised by the doctors to do so. He said that because of this, a popular series of his, ''Drunk Minecraft'', would no longer be produced.<ref>{{cite web|title=MARK HAD A HEART ATTACK?! {{!}} Reading Your Comments #4|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wPjr8sT9t8E|date=November 17, 2015|accessdate=February 6, 2016|last1=Fishbach|first1=Mark Edward|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Fischbach dyed his hair pink for a charity along with [[Jacksepticeye]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M3L74eP-ncg|title=Markiplier with PINK HAIR?!|first=Mark Edward|last=Fishbach|date=September 11, 2015|website=YouTube}}</ref> He later dyed his hair blue in December 2015 and then red in March 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a8E2Kit1Qio|title=Markiplier With RED Hair?!|first=Mark Edward|last=Fishbach|date=March 4, 2016|website=YouTube}}</ref> and back to his natural black hair color on December 30, 2016 in time for 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=snBTH2bIme8|title=THE ULTIMATE BET|first=Mark Edward|last=Fishbach|date=January 4, 2017|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nFischbach co-hosted the 2015 South by Southwest (SXSW) Gaming Awards with ''[[The Legend of Korra]]'' voice actor [[Janet Varney]],<ref>{{cite web|title=South By Southwest Gaming Preview|url=http://www.twcnews.com/tx/austin/news/2015/03/6/south-by-southwest-gaming-preview.html|website=TWC News|publisher=Turner-Warner Cable News|accessdate=April 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804015124/http://www.twcnews.com/tx/austin/news/2015/03/6/south-by-southwest-gaming-preview.html|archive-date=August 4, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and was featured in YouTube's year-end special [[YouTube Rewind]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2015/12/09/youtube-rewind-2015/|title=Watch YouTube\u2019s Biggest Stars Relive 2015|website=Fortune|last1=Addady|first1=Michael|date=December 10, 2015|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Fischbach signed to Revelmode, a subnetwork to [[Maker Studios]], along with other YouTubers such as [[Jacksepticeye]] and [[PewDiePie]]. Revelmode was disbanded in early 2017 as a result of PewDiePie being cut from Maker Studios. He subsequently signed to another Maker Studios sub-network, Polaris.\n\nThroughout 2016, Fischbach moved some of his focus to comedy sketches, showing his aspiration of [[improvisational theatre]]. In 2017, Fischbach posted an interactive ''[[Choose Your Own Adventure]]''-style video titled \"A Date With Markiplier\", which was well received by fans.<ref>{{Citation|last=Markiplier|title=A DATE WITH MARKIPLIER|date=February 14, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yyU_1JD2wuA&t=5s|accessdate=February 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2017/02/15/markiplier-just-put-together-best-dating-adventure-possible/|title=Markiplier Just Put Together The Best Dating Adventure Possible|last1=Sheehan|first1=Gavin|date=February 15, 2017|website=Bleeding Cool Comic Book, Movie, TV News|access-date=February 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2016, Fischbach formed a team, nicknamed \"Teamiplier\", to assist in the creation of his videos and more high-quality sketches, including his girlfriend Amy, and his friends Ethan, Tyler and Kathryn.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fishbach|first=Mark Edward|title=Tyler's First Edit|date=February 23, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=if0csdifkD4|accessdate=February 26, 2017|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 2018, Fischbach announced that his YouTube channel had surpassed 20 million subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2018/03/29/markiplier-20-million-subscribers-tasteful-nudes/|title=Markiplier Hits 20 Million Subscribers, Unveils 'Tasteful Nudes' Charity Calendar|date=March 29, 2018|website=Tubefilter|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, 2018, Fischbach's step-niece, Miranda,<ref>{{cite web|last=Weiss|first=Geoff|url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2018/06/29/markiplier-youtube-break-mourning/|date=June 29, 2018|accessdate=August 15, 2018|website=Tubefilter|title=Markiplier Taking Break From YouTube To Mourn The Loss of His Niece}}</ref> was killed in a car accident at the age of 19.<ref name=\":0\" /> He released a video 5 days later on June 24 titled \"update\" announcing the news and that he would not be able to make videos for a while.<ref>{{Citation|last=Markiplier|title=update|date=June 24, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4eC4MUicWY0|access-date=June 25, 2018}}</ref> Two days later on June 26, Fischbach released a video titled \"Special Message from Miranda's Dad\", where Mark talked more about Miranda and Miranda's dad, Michael, thanking Fischbach's fanbase.<ref>{{Citation|last=Markiplier|title=Special Message from Miranda's Dad|date=June 26, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rkrCQDK1QdA|access-date=June 27, 2018}}</ref> The same day, Mark started a [[GoFundMe]] campaign to pay for funeral expenses for Miranda's family, where the expected goal of $15,000 more than doubled within 9 hours.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gofundme.com/miranda-cracraft-memorial-fund|title=Click here to support Miranda Cracraft Memorial Fund organized by Mark Fischbach|website=gofundme.com|language=en-US|access-date=June 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October of 2019, Fischbach announced a new Choose Your Own Adventure story similar to 2017's ''A Date With Markiplier'', a ''[[YouTube Premium#Content|YouTube Originals]]'' production titled ''A Heist With Markiplier''. Produced by Fischbach and [[Rooster Teeth]], this series contains 31 possible endings and stars other large YouTube creators such as [[Rosanna Pansino]], [[MatPat|Matthew Patrick]], and ''[[Game Grumps]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Spangler |first1=Todd |title=YouTube\u2019s First Interactive Special Stars Markiplier and Has 31 Possible Endings |url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/youtube-markiplier-interactive-special-1203380837/|website=Variety|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 15, 2019, Fischbach launched a new channel with fellow YouTuber Ethan Mark Nestor (CrankGameplays) called ''Unus Annus'' (Latin for 'one year'), a channel that plans to post a single video every day for one year before being deleted along with all of the videos on the channel, with no reuploads of the channel from two of them.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wXnh0h8IT7E Unus Annus] Unus Annus on YouTube. 15 November 2019. Retrieved 15 November 2019.</ref> The channel shot to early success, gaining 1 million subscribers in its first 5 days and over 11.5 million video views in its first week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2019/11/18/markiplier-unus-annus-youtube-channel-ethan-nestor/|title=Markiplier And Ethan Nestor\u2019s New Self-Destructing Vlog Project Nets Nearly 1M Subscribers In 3 Days|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120042017/http://www.tubefilter.com/web/20191120042017oe_/https://www.tubefilter.com/2019/11/18/markiplier-unus-annus-youtube-channel-ethan-nestor/|archive-date=Nov 20, 2019|access-date=Nov 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialblade.com/youtube/channel/UCIcgBZ9hEJxHv6r_jDYOMqg|title=Unus Annus's YouTube Stats (Summary Profile) - Social Blade Stats|website=socialblade.com|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref> As of the 20th of January, the channel has over two million subscribers.\n\n== Other ventures ==\n[[File:Markiplier 2017.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Fischbach in [[Rosemont, Illinois|Rosemont]], [[Illinois]] for his \"You're Welcome Tour\", October 2017]]\nFischbach joined the board of comic book publisher [[Red Giant Entertainment]] in November 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/news/newsfeeds/articles/marketwire/11G026162-001.htm |date=November 12, 2014 |title=Mark 'Markiplier' Fischbach Joins Red Giant Entertainment's Board of Directors: YouTube Superstar Brings Extraordinary New Media Expertise To Board |work=CNN Money |publisher=CNN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112183801/http://money.cnn.com/news/newsfeeds/articles/marketwire/11G026162-001.htm |archive-date=November 12, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In June of that year at the [[San Diego Comic-Con]], he had cohosted a panel with figures from the company including CEO  [[Benny R. Powell]], and writers [[David Campiti]], [[Mort Castle]], [[David Lawrence (writer)|David Lawrence]], and [[Brian Augustyn]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/youtube-star-markiplier-host-red-giant-entertainment-panel-presentation-san-diego-comic-pinksheets-redg-1927081.htm |title=YouTube Star 'Markiplier' to Host Red Giant Entertainment Panel Presentation at San Diego Comic-Con 2014|work=Marketwired |date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> In 2016, it was announced that he would appear in his own line of comics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2016/04/22/marklipier-gets-youtube-viewers-to-revive-red-giant-entertainment-and-launch-the-zwag-box/|title=Markiplier Gets YouTube Viewers To Revive Red Giant Entertainment - And Launch The Zwag Box|date=April 22, 2016|website=Bleeding Cool Comic Book, Movie, TV News|access-date=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFischbach signed with [[William Morris Endeavor]] in late 2016, having expressed interest in branching out from YouTube content.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/markiplier-wme-1201919766/|title=YouTube Star Markiplier Signs With WME (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=November 16, 2016|newspaper=Variety|language=en-US|access-date=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he provided guest vocals in the song \"Smash!\" by [[Starbomb]], which parodies ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'', from their second album ''[[Player Select]]''. The song also received an animated video. Since 2017 he has voiced the character 5.0.5 in the [[Cartoon Network]] series ''[[Villainous (web series)|Villainous]]''.\n\nIn 2018, Markiplier announced the launch of a new fashion band called '''Cloak''', in a joint venture with [[Jacksepticeye]].<ref>https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2018/10/cloak-brand-clothing-announcement</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, in co-production with QCode Media, he appears in the post-apocalyptic audio drama podcast titled ''Edge of Sleep'', portraying the main character as well as being credited as a producer.\n\n=== Tours ===\n\nIn 2017, he embarked on his first improv tour, known as the \"You're Welcome Tour\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2017/09/06/markiplier-youre-welcome-tour/|title=YouTube Star Markiplier Will Bring His Comedy Show Across The US And Europe With 31-Show Tour - Tubefilter|date=September 6, 2017|work=Tubefilter|access-date=May 3, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> along with Ethan Nestor (CrankGameplays), Wade Barnes (LordMinion777), Tyler Scheid (Apocalypto12) and Bob Muyskens (muyskerm), initially on a short four-date trip in mid-2017 before stretching to a full tour across North America, Australia<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://press-start.com.au/news/2018/02/26/youtuber-markiplier-touring-australia-year/|title=YouTuber Markiplier Is Touring Australia This Year|date=February 26, 2018|work=Press Start Australia - Bringing The Best Of Video Games & Gaming To Australia|access-date=May 3, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and Europe in October 2017 through to 2018.\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nFischbach has done multiple charity streams and fundraisers with other YouTubers, friends and by himself. With the support of his fans, he has been able to donate to many different charities that benefit many different interests. ''Forbes'' reported in 2017 that Fischbach and his fans had helped raise roughly $3 million for charity in past fundraising streams.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2017/11/29/markiplier-raises-422000-save-the-children/|title=Uber-Charitable Markiplier Raises $422,000 During 'Save The Children' Stream - Tubefilter|date=November 29, 2017|work=Tubefilter|access-date=April 30, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> The site Tiltify.com, with which Fischbach has partnered to collect donations on several occasions, lists the total amount raised on his current profile as $1,919,154.96 as of January 25, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tiltify.com/@markiplier/profile|title=About Markiplier|access-date=January 25, 2020|website=tiltify.com}}</ref> Separately he also created a sock bundle of \"Markisocks\", with all proceeds going to the charity \"The [[Epidermolysis Bullosa]] Medical Research Foundation\" (EBMRF) during a 24-hour sale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://represent.com/markisocks|title=Markiplier's Official Charity 'Markisocks'|last=Represent.com|website=represent.com|language=en|access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> In March 2018, in celebration of surpassing the 20 million subscriber milestone, Fischbach announced that he would donate all proceeds from a 48-hour sale of his newly created \"Tasteful Nudes\" Charity Calendar to the [[Cancer Research Institute]]. Calendar sales raised $492,819 for the charity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://happiful.com/top-youtuber-markiplier-raises-500-000-in-just-48-for-cancer-research/|title=Top YouTuber Markiplier Raises $500,000 in just 48 Hours for Cancer Research|date=April 11, 2018|website=Happiful Magazine|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Charity LiveStreams/Videos and Totals\n!Date\n!Charity\n!Total Funds\n|-\n|July 2012\n|Child's Play\n|$1,000.00\n|-\n|February 2013\n|[[Cancer Research Institute]]\n|$8,047.00<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cancerresearch.org/immunotherapy/stories/donors-and-supporters/mark-fischbach|title=Mark Fischbach|website=Cancer Research Institute|access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|February 2015\n|Depression and Bipolar Support Association\n|$82,003.00<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gofundme.com/mwujn0|title=Click here to support Markiplier's Charity Campaign organized by Mark Fischbach|website=gofundme.com|language=en-US|access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|February 2017\n|[[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]]\n|$115,717.00\n|-\n|March 2017\n|[[Charity: Water]]\n|$254,649.00\n|-\n|April 2017\n|[[Environmental Defense Fund]]\n|$123,111.00\n|-\n|May 2017\n|Game Changer\n|$198,378.00\n|-\n|August 2017\n|[[Joyful Heart Foundation]]\n