{"title_page": "Amelle Berrabah", "text_new": "{{short description|English singer and songwriter}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Amelle Berrabah\n|image           = Amelle Berrabah crop Chester Rocks 2011.jpg\n|caption         = Berrabah performing live in 2011 as part of the Sugababes\n|background      = solo_singer\n|Birth name      =\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1984|4|22|df=y}}\n|origin          = [[Aldershot]], Hampshire,<br /> England, United Kingdom\n|genre           = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[dance-pop]]\n|occupation      = Singer, songwriter\n|years_active    = 2003\u2013present\n|associated_acts = [[Sugababes]], [[Tinchy Stryder]]\n|label           = [[Island Records|Island]], [[RCA Records|RCA]], HitMan\n|website         =\n}}\n'''Amelle Berrabah''' (born 22 April 1984) is an English singer, songwriter and former member of the [[Sugababes]] who replaced founding member [[Mutya Buena]] in the group in December 2005. She achieved a solo number one single in 2009 after collaborating with [[Tinchy Stryder]] on their single \"[[Never Leave You]]\", which made her the first and, to date, only member of the Sugababes to achieve a number one single outside of the group.\n\n==Life and career==\nBerrabah was born in [[Aldershot]], Hampshire to [[British Moroccans|Moroccan]] parents. She has four sisters, younger sister Samiya, older sisters Laila, Zakiya and Nora and a brother, Khaled. Amelle is also closely related to her cousins Elmokhtar, Samira and Zahra Berrabah.<ref name=aldershot/><ref name=firstarrest/><ref name=secondarrest/><ref name=dubai>{{cite web |url=http://gulfnews.com/about-gulf-news/al-nisr-portfolio/tabloid/articles/amelle-berrabah-in-the-spotlight-1.17172 |title=Amelle Berrabah in the spotlight |work=Gulf News |date=7 May 2008 |accessdate=31 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121070813/http://gulfnews.com/about-gulf-news/al-nisr-portfolio/tabloid/articles/amelle-berrabah-in-the-spotlight-1.17172 |archivedate=21 November 2010  }}</ref> Her family owned a [[kebab]] shop in Aldershot.<ref name=biggest>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/mar/17/popandrock.girlsaloud|title=We're the biggest ...|first=Chris|last=Salmon|date=17 March 2008|accessdate=5 November 2009|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114095020/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/mar/17/popandrock.girlsaloud|archivedate=14 January 2014}}</ref> Berrabah's father died of cancer in 2002.<ref>{{citation|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8587411.stm|publisher=BBC |date=30 March 2010|accessdate=3 April 2010|first=Neil|last=Bowdler | title=Sugababe Amelle talks of cancer loss| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100402234901/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8587411.stm| archivedate= 2 April 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Berrabah attended [[Alderwood Senior School|The Connaught School]] in Aldershot and the [[Academy of Contemporary Music]] in [[Guildford]], the latter on the merit of a scholarship. It was then that she met her managers and formed the group Boo2, with her sister, Samiya and began looking for record contract opportunities.<ref name=metro/> She won ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' magazine\u2019s ''Star Search'' in 2003 that gave her the chance to be the lead singer of a new group and had performed at [[Party in the Park]] as well.<ref name=aldershot>{{citation|url=http://www.gethampshire.co.uk/news/s/27086_aldershots_amelle_is_the_new_sugababe |title=Aldershot\u2019s Amelle is the new Sugababe |date=29 December 2005 |accessdate=5 November 2009 |publisher=S&B media |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107181406/http://www.gethampshire.co.uk/news/s/27086_aldershots_amelle_is_the_new_sugababe |archivedate=7 January 2009  }}</ref><ref name=metro/>\n\n===2006-2008: Success with the Sugababes===\n[[Image:Sugababes 2006 Hammersmith Appollo.jpg|thumb|left|Berrabah in 2006, performing on the Taller In More Ways Tour]]\n\nFollowing Mutya Buena's departure from Sugababes, Berrabah was brought in as a replacement by the group's management. Their manager had seen Boo2 perform at an American showcase a few years prior in 2003 and Berrabah had impressed him. As soon as Buena left, he gave Berrabah a call about the opportunity and got her to record three songs to audition for remaining members [[Keisha Buchanan]] and [[Heidi Range]]. They liked the demos and Berrabah was then announced as the newest member of the trio.<ref name=aldershot/><ref name=metro>{{citation|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/fame/interviews/article.html?in_article_id=10618|title=60 SECONDS: Amelle Berrabah|first=Andrew|last=Williams|date= 6 March 2006|accessdate=5 November 2009}}</ref> The first single to feature Berrabah's vocals, \"[[Red Dress (song)|Red Dress]]\", entered the [[UK Singles Chart]] at number four.<ref name=firstarrest/> ''[[Taller in More Ways]]'' was re-released in early 2006 with re-recorded vocals by Berrabah. Because of the hastiness of the replacement, she could only re-record vocals for three of the tracks on the album.<ref name=metro/> She also contributed the song, \"Now You're Gone\" to the new track listing. They performed the 2007 [[Comic Relief (charity)|Comic Relief]] single with fellow girlband, [[Girls Aloud]], \"Walk This Way\",<ref>{{citation|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6317377.stm|title=Girl groups get red noses rolling|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 November 2009|date=31 January 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69lXaZa7l?url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6317377.stm|archivedate=8 August 2012}}</ref> which went to number one.<ref>{{citation|url=http://theofficialcharts.com/all_singles_song.php?id=1062|title=Sugababes vs Girls Aloud \u2013 Walk This Way|accessdate=29 November 2009|publisher=[[The Official UK Charts Company]]}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> On 28 April 2007, Berrabah was arrested over allegations that she had assaulted a girl on the dancefloor in a club.<ref name=firstarrest>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/apr/30/news.rosieswash|title=Sugababes star arrested on assault charge|first=Rosie|last=Swash|accessdate=5 November 2009|date=30 April 2007|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141003102912/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/apr/30/news.rosieswash|archivedate=3 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=secondarrest/> No charges were brought.<ref name=biggest/>\n\nThe first single from their album ''Change'', the [[Dr. Luke]] produced \"About You Now\", topped the UK singles chart for four weeks. In October 2007, ''Change'' became the group's second [[UK Albums Chart]] number one, giving the group the top positions on the singles and albums charts simultaneously.<ref name=secondarrest/> Berrabah was credited with co-writing five songs on the album. Berrabah was arrested again on 10 January 2008 on suspicion of causing criminal damage and a public order offence. The arrest was made in connection with an alleged attack on a car in her hometown of Aldershot on 9 January 2008.<ref name=secondarrest>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jan/11/urban.ukcrime|title=Sugababe Amelle Berrabah arrested|first=Adam|last=Silverstein|date=11 January 2008|accessdate=5 November 2009|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114092420/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jan/11/urban.ukcrime|archivedate=14 January 2014}}</ref> The charges were quickly dropped when it was revealed that she was not even in town at the time.<ref name=biggest/> Despite announcing a break after the Change tour, the group quickly began working on ''[[Catfights and Spotlights]]'', which was released in late 2008 and became their lowest charting album at the time.\n\n===2009-2011: Solo success and group turmoil===\nAfter the commercial disappointment of ''Catfights and Spotlights'', the group began working on a new album, ''Sweet 7'', signing with [[Roc Nation]] and working with their in-house producers in the US.<ref name=\"ds-rocafella\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/a154140/sugababes-sign-up-to-jay-z-label.html |title=Music \u2013 News \u2013 Sugababes 'sign up to Jay-Z label' \u2013 Digital Spy |publisher=Digital Spy<! |date=27 April 2009 |accessdate=6 July 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090601235833/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/a154140/sugababes-sign-up-to-jay-z-label.html| archivedate= 1 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Around this time, Berrabah also featured on \"Never Leave You\" by Tinchy Stryder in 2009, the single debuted at number one in the UK.<ref name=acharts/> The first single, \"Get Sexy\", from ''Sweet 7'' was released soon after and reached number 2 on the UK charts.  Prior to shooting the video for the second single, [[RedOne]] production \"[[About a Girl (Sugababes song)|About a Girl]]\", Berrabah was rumoured to have left the group. She had missed two engagements promoting the album. It was later revealed that in fact Buchanan had been removed due to disagreements with Berrabah and Range, and replaced by [[Jade Ewen]]. Berrabah and Range had earlier quit the Sugababes claiming that they could not work in the group any longer, their management then retained them and removed Buchanan instead.<ref name=dee>{{citation|title=Sugababes: so do they still exist or not?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/sep/22/sugababes-split-up-keisha|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|date=22 September 2009|first=Johnny|last=Dee|accessdate=5 November 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811113059/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/sep/22/sugababes-split-up-keisha|archivedate=11 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=roc>{{citation|title=Sugababes' Keisha sacked from band|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/sep/22/sugababes-keisha-sacked|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|date=22 September 2009|first=Sean|last=Michaels|accessdate=5 November 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007192422/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/sep/22/sugababes-keisha-sacked|archivedate=7 October 2015}}</ref> Following these events, Berrabah checked into a European health clinic for a three-week stay, citing \"severe nervous exhaustion\".<ref>{{citation|title=Sugababes' Amelle suffering from 'severe nervous exhaustion'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/oct/16/sugababes-amelle|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|date=16 October 2009|first=Tim|last=Jonze|accessdate=5 November 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091019035959/http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2009/oct/16/sugababes-amelle| archivedate= 19 October 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> ''Sweet 7'' was released in early 2010 after multiple delays from late 2009. It charted at number 14 on the UK Albums Chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a209894/lady-gaga-reclaims-uk-album-top-spot.html |title=Music \u2013 News \u2013 Lady GaGa reclaims UK album top spot |work=Digital Spy |date=21 March 2010 |accessdate=27 April 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69i3wgf14?url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a209894/lady-gaga-reclaims-uk-album-top-spot.html |archivedate=6 August 2012  }}</ref>\n\nThe Sugababes began recording a new studio album soon after,<ref name=\"digitalspy.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a215683/sugababes-begin-work-on-new-album.html |title=Music \u2013 News \u2013 Sugababes begin work on new album |work=Digital Spy |date=21 April 2010 |accessdate=27 April 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100424213111/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a215683/sugababes-begin-work-on-new-album.html| archivedate= 24 April 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> leaving Island Records for a distribution deal with [[RCA Records]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaessentials.co.uk/2011/07/media-essentials-sugababes-sign-to-sony-rca/ |title=Sugababes Sign To Sony RCA |publisher=Media Essentials |date=7 June 2011 |accessdate=30 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830112717/http://www.mediaessentials.co.uk/2011/07/media-essentials-sugababes-sign-to-sony-rca/ |archivedate=30 August 2011  }}</ref> The planned first single, \"[[Freedom (Sugababes song)|Freedom]]\" was released for free in August after it failed to gain any traction in airplay. A few months after the release, Range explained that the Sugababes were taking a break while they pursued individual endeavours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itn.co.uk/home/36182/Heidi+Range+27Sugababes+have+not+split27 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=24 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120919011000/http://www.itn.co.uk/home/36182/Heidi%2BRange%2B27Sugababes%2Bhave%2Bnot%2Bsplit27 |archivedate=19 September 2012  }}</ref>\n\n===2011-present: Solo career===\nBerrabah began working on solo material in 2011 with producer [[Pete Kirtley]], who had previously produced her co-writing contribution, \"Now You're Gone\" from ''Taller in More Ways''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4music.com/news/news/2697/Has-Sugababes-Amelle-gone-solo |title=4Music \u2013 News \u2013 General \u2013 Has Sugababes' Amelle gone solo? |publisher=4Music |date=13 January 2012 |accessdate=18 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203073512/http://www.4music.com/news/news/2697/Has-Sugababes-Amelle-gone-solo |archivedate=3 December 2013  }}</ref> and material by Boo2. In January 2012, Berrabah confirmed she'd been working on a solo album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4music.com/news/news/2697/Has-Sugababes-Amelle-gone-solo |title=Amelle Berrabah is working on solo record |publisher=Popjustice |date=13 January 2012 |accessdate=5 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203073512/http://www.4music.com/news/news/2697/Has-Sugababes-Amelle-gone-solo |archivedate=3 December 2013  }}</ref> A clip of the song \"God Won't Save You Now\" was posted to the [[SoundCloud]] account of Kirtley and fellow producer Sacha {{proper name|Collisson}}, who are collectively known as D-B-X.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/d-b-x/dbx-ft-amelle-god-wont-save-u |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222320/http://soundcloud.com/d-b-x/dbx-ft-amelle-god-wont-save-u |archivedate=2 December 2013  }}</ref> The full song leaked a few weeks later. On 6 March 2012, it was reported Berrabah had gone to [[Los Angeles]] to record new material for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popjustice.com/thenews/amelle-berrabah-is-working-on-a-solo-record/70593/|title=Amelle Berrabah enjoys workout|publisher=[[The Sun (magazine)|The Sun]]|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=5 January 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202230402/http://www.popjustice.com/thenews/amelle-berrabah-is-working-on-a-solo-record/70593/|archivedate=2 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2110922/Amelle-Berrabah-shows-washboard-stomach-crop-maintains-slim-figure-morning-hike.html|title=Amelle Berrabah shows off her washboard stomach in a crop top as she maintains her slim figure on a morning hike|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=5 January 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130420074953/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2110922/Amelle-Berrabah-shows-washboard-stomach-crop-maintains-slim-figure-morning-hike.html|archivedate=20 April 2013}}</ref> In July 2012, Berrabah told Journalist Mark Boardman \"I've written every song on the album apart from two,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://markmeets.com/#/amelle-berrabah-interview/4576519773/|title=Amelle Berrabah talks debut album|publisher=MarkMeets|date=July 2012|accessdate=5 January 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113055356/http://markmeets.com/#/amelle-berrabah-interview/4576519773/|archivedate=13 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Berrabah was featured on the song \"Ordinary Me\" by rapper Mr. Bigz on the latter's mixtape ''The Bigz Bang Theory'' in late 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/MrBigzOfficial/status/276159982918057985 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=7 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203044904/https://twitter.com/MrBigzOfficial/status/276159982918057985 |archivedate=3 December 2013  }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Berrabah confirmed she'd nearly completed work on her solo album, and was looking to release the collection some time in the summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a481017/sugababes-amelle-teases-solo-album-ive-been-a-perfectionist.html|title=Sugababes' Amelle teases solo album: 'I've been a perfectionist'|website=[[Digital Spy]]|date=13 May 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730154511/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a481017/sugababes-amelle-teases-solo-album-ive-been-a-perfectionist.html|archivedate=30 July 2013}}</ref> Berrabah teamed up with [[United Kingdom|British]] DJ Adam J for his single \"[[Love (Is All We Need)]]\", and featured production team The Nightcrashers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://idolator.com/7466499/adam-j-sugababes-amelle-berrabah-love-is-all-we-need-lyric-video|title=Adam J & Sugababes' Amelle Record Clubby \"Love Is All We Need\": Watch The Lyric Video|publisher=Idolator|date=25 June 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730080425/http://idolator.com/7466499/adam-j-sugababes-amelle-berrabah-love-is-all-we-need-lyric-video|archivedate=30 July 2013}}</ref> Berrabah released another single, \"Summertime\", on 21 September 2014. The video premi\u00e8red on Vevo on 9 August.  During this time, Berrabah also made a series of appearances on reality competitions, competing in the BBC celebrity gymnastics show ''[[Tumble (TV series)|Tumble]]'' in mid-2014 and ''[[Celebrity Masterchef]]'' in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/music/musicnews/amelle-berrabah-emma-samms-sign-gymnastics-show-486159.html|title=Amelle Berrabah And Emma Samms Sign Up for Gymnastics Show|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108151806/http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/music/musicnews/amelle-berrabah-emma-samms-sign-gymnastics-show-486159.html|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masterchef.com/celebrity-masterchef|title=Welcome to MasterChef UK|website=MasterChef UK|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615032209/http://www.masterchef.com/celebrity-masterchef|archive-date=15 June 2016}}</ref>  She made her theatre debut in 2019, with the [[Nick Winston]]-directed [[jukebox musical]] ''Club Tropicana''.<ref name=\"tropicana\">https://www.thestage.co.uk/features/interviews/2019/sugababes-amelle-berrabah-musical-theatre-club-tropicana/</ref>\n\nBerrabah married Marcio Sousa Rosa on 17 October 2014.<ref name=\"Amelle announces marriage on official twitter.\">https://twitter.com/Amelle_Berrabah/status/523207635190157312</ref> On 25 December 2017, Berrabah revealed on her Twitter account that she is pregnant.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://twitter.com/Amelle_B_SRosa/status/945409454350176257|title=I\u2019m eating for 2! So I get a pass! Lol|last=Martin|first=Lara|date=25 December 2017|work=[[Twitter]]|publisher=[[Amelle]]|access-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426133728/https://twitter.com/Amelle_B_SRosa/status/945409454350176257|archivedate=26 April 2018}}</ref> She gave birth to her first child on 10 June 2018, a daughter named Amirah.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/Amelle_B_SRosa/status/1005818342861664257/photo/1|title=Our daughter... Amirah Hope Sousa Rosa|date=10 June 2018|work=[[Twitter]]|publisher=[[Amelle]]|access-date=10 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"tropicana\" />\n\n==Discography==\n{{see also|Sugababes discography}}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n!colspan=\"3\"| Chart positions\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! width=40|<small> [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]</small><br /><ref name=acharts>{{citation|url=http://acharts.us/song/47180|title=Tinchy Stryder and Amelle Berrabah \u2013 Never Leave You|publisher=\u03b1Charts.us|accessdate=28 January 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904171820/http://acharts.us/song/47180 |archivedate=4 September 2011}}</ref>\n! width=40|<small> [[Irish Singles Chart|IRE]]</small><br /><ref name=acharts/>\n!style=\"width:4em;font-size:85%\"|[[Euro Hot 100|EU]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=the saturdays|chart=all}}|title=Amelle Berrabah > Album & Song Chart History > European Hot 100|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Company|accessdate=15 November 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n|| 2009\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Never Leave You]]\" <small>(with [[Tinchy Stryder]])</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n||''[[Catch 22 (Tinchy Stryder album)|Catch 22]]''\n|-\n|| 2013\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Love (Is All We Need)]]\" <small>(with Adam J and Nightcrashers)</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n||Non-album single\n|-\n|| 2014\n|align=\"left\"|\"Summertime\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n||TBA\n|-\n|}\n\n===Other appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of guest appearances, with other performing artists, showing year released and album name\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Other performer(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Album\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Til the End\"\n|2010\n|Tinchy Stryder\n|''[[Third Strike (Tinchy Stryder album)|Third Strike]]''\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Ordinary Me\"\n|2013\n|Bigz\n|''The Bigz Bang Theory''<br><small>(Mixtape)</small>\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of featured music videos, showing year released and director\n! Title\n! Year\n! Director(s)\n! Ref.\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | \"Never Leave You\"<br /><small>(with Tinchy Stryder)</small>\n| 2009\n| Emil Nava\n|<ref>[http://www.promonews.tv/2009/07/22/tinchy-stryder-feat-amelle%E2%80%99s-never-leave-you-by-emil-nava/ Tinchy Stryder feat Amelle\u2019s Never Leave You by Emil Nava] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528230106/http://www.promonews.tv/2009/07/22/tinchy-stryder-feat-amelle%E2%80%99s-never-leave-you-by-emil-nava/ |date=28 May 2012 }}. www.promonews.tv. Wednesday, 22 July 2009. Retrieved Wednesday, 2 November 2011.</ref>\n|-\n\n| align=\"center\" | \"Love Is All We Need\"<br /><small>(with Adam J and Nightcrashers)</small>\n| 2013\n| N/A\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{commons category|Amelle Berrabah}}\n* {{Facebook|officialamelleberrabah|Amelle Berrabah}}\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=amelle-berrabah-mn0001096227|Amelle Berrabah}}\n* {{IMDb name|2184377|Amelle Berrabah}}\n\n{{Amelle Berrabah}}\n{{Sugababes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berrabah, Amelle}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:English people of Moroccan descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Aldershot]]\n[[Category:Sugababes members]]\n[[Category:English female pop singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English singer and songwriter}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Amelle Berrabah\n|image           = Amelle Berrabah crop Chester Rocks 2011.jpg\n|caption         = Berrabah performing live in 2011 as part of the Sugababes\n|background      = solo_singer\n|Birth name      =\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1984|4|22|df=y}}\n|origin          = [[Aldershot]], Hampshire,<br /> England, United Kingdom\n|genre           = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[dance-pop]]\n|occupation      = Singer, songwriter\n|years_active    = 2003\u2013present\n|associated_acts = [[Sugababes]], [[Tinchy Stryder]]\n|label           = [[Island Records|Island]], [[RCA Records|RCA]], HitMan\n|website         =\n}}\n'''Amelle Berrabah''' (born 22 April 1984) is an English singer, songwriter and former member of the [[Sugababes]] who replaced founding member [[Mutya Buena]] in the group in December 2005. She achieved a solo number one single in 2009 after collaborating with [[Tinchy Stryder]] on their single \"[[Never Leave You]]\", which made her the first and, to date, only member of the Sugababes to achieve a number one single outside of the group.\n\n==Life and career==\nBerrabah was born in [[Aldershot]], Hampshire to [[British Moroccans|Moroccan]] parents. She has four sisters, younger sister Samiya, older sisters Laila, Zakiya and Nora and a brother, Khaled.<ref name=aldershot/><ref name=firstarrest/><ref name=secondarrest/><ref name=dubai>{{cite web |url=http://gulfnews.com/about-gulf-news/al-nisr-portfolio/tabloid/articles/amelle-berrabah-in-the-spotlight-1.17172 |title=Amelle Berrabah in the spotlight |work=Gulf News |date=7 May 2008 |accessdate=31 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121070813/http://gulfnews.com/about-gulf-news/al-nisr-portfolio/tabloid/articles/amelle-berrabah-in-the-spotlight-1.17172 |archivedate=21 November 2010  }}</ref> Her family owned a [[kebab]] shop in Aldershot.<ref name=biggest>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/mar/17/popandrock.girlsaloud|title=We're the biggest ...|first=Chris|last=Salmon|date=17 March 2008|accessdate=5 November 2009|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114095020/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/mar/17/popandrock.girlsaloud|archivedate=14 January 2014}}</ref> Berrabah's father died of cancer in 2002.<ref>{{citation|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8587411.stm|publisher=BBC |date=30 March 2010|accessdate=3 April 2010|first=Neil|last=Bowdler | title=Sugababe Amelle talks of cancer loss| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100402234901/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8587411.stm| archivedate= 2 April 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Berrabah attended [[Alderwood Senior School|The Connaught School]] in Aldershot and the [[Academy of Contemporary Music]] in [[Guildford]], the latter on the merit of a scholarship. It was then that she met her managers and formed the group Boo2, with her sister, Samiya and began looking for record contract opportunities.<ref name=metro/> She won ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' magazine\u2019s ''Star Search'' in 2003 that gave her the chance to be the lead singer of a new group and had performed at [[Party in the Park]] as well.<ref name=aldershot>{{citation|url=http://www.gethampshire.co.uk/news/s/27086_aldershots_amelle_is_the_new_sugababe |title=Aldershot\u2019s Amelle is the new Sugababe |date=29 December 2005 |accessdate=5 November 2009 |publisher=S&B media |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107181406/http://www.gethampshire.co.uk/news/s/27086_aldershots_amelle_is_the_new_sugababe |archivedate=7 January 2009  }}</ref><ref name=metro/>\n\n===2006-2008: Success with the Sugababes===\n[[Image:Sugababes 2006 Hammersmith Appollo.jpg|thumb|left|Berrabah in 2006, performing on the Taller In More Ways Tour]]\n\nFollowing Mutya Buena's departure from Sugababes, Berrabah was brought in as a replacement by the group's management. Their manager had seen Boo2 perform at an American showcase a few years prior in 2003 and Berrabah had impressed him. As soon as Buena left, he gave Berrabah a call about the opportunity and got her to record three songs to audition for remaining members [[Keisha Buchanan]] and [[Heidi Range]]. They liked the demos and Berrabah was then announced as the newest member of the trio.<ref name=aldershot/><ref name=metro>{{citation|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/fame/interviews/article.html?in_article_id=10618|title=60 SECONDS: Amelle Berrabah|first=Andrew|last=Williams|date= 6 March 2006|accessdate=5 November 2009}}</ref> The first single to feature Berrabah's vocals, \"[[Red Dress (song)|Red Dress]]\", entered the [[UK Singles Chart]] at number four.<ref name=firstarrest/> ''[[Taller in More Ways]]'' was re-released in early 2006 with re-recorded vocals by Berrabah. Because of the hastiness of the replacement, she could only re-record vocals for three of the tracks on the album.<ref name=metro/> She also contributed the song, \"Now You're Gone\" to the new track listing. They performed the 2007 [[Comic Relief (charity)|Comic Relief]] single with fellow girlband, [[Girls Aloud]], \"Walk This Way\",<ref>{{citation|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6317377.stm|title=Girl groups get red noses rolling|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 November 2009|date=31 January 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69lXaZa7l?url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6317377.stm|archivedate=8 August 2012}}</ref> which went to number one.<ref>{{citation|url=http://theofficialcharts.com/all_singles_song.php?id=1062|title=Sugababes vs Girls Aloud \u2013 Walk This Way|accessdate=29 November 2009|publisher=[[The Official UK Charts Company]]}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> On 28 April 2007, Berrabah was arrested over allegations that she had assaulted a girl on the dancefloor in a club.<ref name=firstarrest>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/apr/30/news.rosieswash|title=Sugababes star arrested on assault charge|first=Rosie|last=Swash|accessdate=5 November 2009|date=30 April 2007|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141003102912/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/apr/30/news.rosieswash|archivedate=3 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=secondarrest/> No charges were brought.<ref name=biggest/>\n\nThe first single from their album ''Change'', the [[Dr. Luke]] produced \"About You Now\", topped the UK singles chart for four weeks. In October 2007, ''Change'' became the group's second [[UK Albums Chart]] number one, giving the group the top positions on the singles and albums charts simultaneously.<ref name=secondarrest/> Berrabah was credited with co-writing five songs on the album. Berrabah was arrested again on 10 January 2008 on suspicion of causing criminal damage and a public order offence. The arrest was made in connection with an alleged attack on a car in her hometown of Aldershot on 9 January 2008.<ref name=secondarrest>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jan/11/urban.ukcrime|title=Sugababe Amelle Berrabah arrested|first=Adam|last=Silverstein|date=11 January 2008|accessdate=5 November 2009|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114092420/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jan/11/urban.ukcrime|archivedate=14 January 2014}}</ref> The charges were quickly dropped when it was revealed that she was not even in town at the time.<ref name=biggest/> Despite announcing a break after the Change tour, the group quickly began working on ''[[Catfights and Spotlights]]'', which was released in late 2008 and became their lowest charting album at the time.\n\n===2009-2011: Solo success and group turmoil===\nAfter the commercial disappointment of ''Catfights and Spotlights'', the group began working on a new album, ''Sweet 7'', signing with [[Roc Nation]] and working with their in-house producers in the US.<ref name=\"ds-rocafella\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/a154140/sugababes-sign-up-to-jay-z-label.html |title=Music \u2013 News \u2013 Sugababes 'sign up to Jay-Z label' \u2013 Digital Spy |publisher=Digital Spy<! |date=27 April 2009 |accessdate=6 July 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090601235833/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/a154140/sugababes-sign-up-to-jay-z-label.html| archivedate= 1 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Around this time, Berrabah also featured on \"Never Leave You\" by Tinchy Stryder in 2009, the single debuted at number one in the UK.<ref name=acharts/> The first single, \"Get Sexy\", from ''Sweet 7'' was released soon after and reached number 2 on the UK charts.  Prior to shooting the video for the second single, [[RedOne]] production \"[[About a Girl (Sugababes song)|About a Girl]]\", Berrabah was rumoured to have left the group. She had missed two engagements promoting the album. It was later revealed that in fact Buchanan had been removed due to disagreements with Berrabah and Range, and replaced by [[Jade Ewen]]. Berrabah and Range had earlier quit the Sugababes claiming that they could not work in the group any longer, their management then retained them and removed Buchanan instead.<ref name=dee>{{citation|title=Sugababes: so do they still exist or not?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/sep/22/sugababes-split-up-keisha|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|date=22 September 2009|first=Johnny|last=Dee|accessdate=5 November 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811113059/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/sep/22/sugababes-split-up-keisha|archivedate=11 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=roc>{{citation|title=Sugababes' Keisha sacked from band|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/sep/22/sugababes-keisha-sacked|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|date=22 September 2009|first=Sean|last=Michaels|accessdate=5 November 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007192422/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/sep/22/sugababes-keisha-sacked|archivedate=7 October 2015}}</ref> Following these events, Berrabah checked into a European health clinic for a three-week stay, citing \"severe nervous exhaustion\".<ref>{{citation|title=Sugababes' Amelle suffering from 'severe nervous exhaustion'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/oct/16/sugababes-amelle|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|date=16 October 2009|first=Tim|last=Jonze|accessdate=5 November 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091019035959/http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2009/oct/16/sugababes-amelle| archivedate= 19 October 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> ''Sweet 7'' was released in early 2010 after multiple delays from late 2009. It charted at number 14 on the UK Albums Chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a209894/lady-gaga-reclaims-uk-album-top-spot.html |title=Music \u2013 News \u2013 Lady GaGa reclaims UK album top spot |work=Digital Spy |date=21 March 2010 |accessdate=27 April 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69i3wgf14?url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a209894/lady-gaga-reclaims-uk-album-top-spot.html |archivedate=6 August 2012  }}</ref>\n\nThe Sugababes began recording a new studio album soon after,<ref name=\"digitalspy.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a215683/sugababes-begin-work-on-new-album.html |title=Music \u2013 News \u2013 Sugababes begin work on new album |work=Digital Spy |date=21 April 2010 |accessdate=27 April 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100424213111/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a215683/sugababes-begin-work-on-new-album.html| archivedate= 24 April 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> leaving Island Records for a distribution deal with [[RCA Records]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaessentials.co.uk/2011/07/media-essentials-sugababes-sign-to-sony-rca/ |title=Sugababes Sign To Sony RCA |publisher=Media Essentials |date=7 June 2011 |accessdate=30 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830112717/http://www.mediaessentials.co.uk/2011/07/media-essentials-sugababes-sign-to-sony-rca/ |archivedate=30 August 2011  }}</ref> The planned first single, \"[[Freedom (Sugababes song)|Freedom]]\" was released for free in August after it failed to gain any traction in airplay. A few months after the release, Range explained that the Sugababes were taking a break while they pursued individual endeavours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itn.co.uk/home/36182/Heidi+Range+27Sugababes+have+not+split27 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=24 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120919011000/http://www.itn.co.uk/home/36182/Heidi%2BRange%2B27Sugababes%2Bhave%2Bnot%2Bsplit27 |archivedate=19 September 2012  }}</ref>\n\n===2011-present: Solo career===\nBerrabah began working on solo material in 2011 with producer [[Pete Kirtley]], who had previously produced her co-writing contribution, \"Now You're Gone\" from ''Taller in More Ways''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4music.com/news/news/2697/Has-Sugababes-Amelle-gone-solo |title=4Music \u2013 News \u2013 General \u2013 Has Sugababes' Amelle gone solo? |publisher=4Music |date=13 January 2012 |accessdate=18 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203073512/http://www.4music.com/news/news/2697/Has-Sugababes-Amelle-gone-solo |archivedate=3 December 2013  }}</ref> and material by Boo2. In January 2012, Berrabah confirmed she'd been working on a solo album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4music.com/news/news/2697/Has-Sugababes-Amelle-gone-solo |title=Amelle Berrabah is working on solo record |publisher=Popjustice |date=13 January 2012 |accessdate=5 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203073512/http://www.4music.com/news/news/2697/Has-Sugababes-Amelle-gone-solo |archivedate=3 December 2013  }}</ref> A clip of the song \"God Won't Save You Now\" was posted to the [[SoundCloud]] account of Kirtley and fellow producer Sacha {{proper name|Collisson}}, who are collectively known as D-B-X.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/d-b-x/dbx-ft-amelle-god-wont-save-u |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222320/http://soundcloud.com/d-b-x/dbx-ft-amelle-god-wont-save-u |archivedate=2 December 2013  }}</ref> The full song leaked a few weeks later. On 6 March 2012, it was reported Berrabah had gone to [[Los Angeles]] to record new material for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popjustice.com/thenews/amelle-berrabah-is-working-on-a-solo-record/70593/|title=Amelle Berrabah enjoys workout|publisher=[[The Sun (magazine)|The Sun]]|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=5 January 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202230402/http://www.popjustice.com/thenews/amelle-berrabah-is-working-on-a-solo-record/70593/|archivedate=2 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2110922/Amelle-Berrabah-shows-washboard-stomach-crop-maintains-slim-figure-morning-hike.html|title=Amelle Berrabah shows off her washboard stomach in a crop top as she maintains her slim figure on a morning hike|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=5 January 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130420074953/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2110922/Amelle-Berrabah-shows-washboard-stomach-crop-maintains-slim-figure-morning-hike.html|archivedate=20 April 2013}}</ref> In July 2012, Berrabah told Journalist Mark Boardman \"I've written every song on the album apart from two,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://markmeets.com/#/amelle-berrabah-interview/4576519773/|title=Amelle Berrabah talks debut album|publisher=MarkMeets|date=July 2012|accessdate=5 January 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113055356/http://markmeets.com/#/amelle-berrabah-interview/4576519773/|archivedate=13 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Berrabah was featured on the song \"Ordinary Me\" by rapper Mr. Bigz on the latter's mixtape ''The Bigz Bang Theory'' in late 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/MrBigzOfficial/status/276159982918057985 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=7 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203044904/https://twitter.com/MrBigzOfficial/status/276159982918057985 |archivedate=3 December 2013  }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Berrabah confirmed she'd nearly completed work on her solo album, and was looking to release the collection some time in the summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a481017/sugababes-amelle-teases-solo-album-ive-been-a-perfectionist.html|title=Sugababes' Amelle teases solo album: 'I've been a perfectionist'|website=[[Digital Spy]]|date=13 May 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730154511/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a481017/sugababes-amelle-teases-solo-album-ive-been-a-perfectionist.html|archivedate=30 July 2013}}</ref> Berrabah teamed up with [[United Kingdom|British]] DJ Adam J for his single \"[[Love (Is All We Need)]]\", and featured production team The Nightcrashers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://idolator.com/7466499/adam-j-sugababes-amelle-berrabah-love-is-all-we-need-lyric-video|title=Adam J & Sugababes' Amelle Record Clubby \"Love Is All We Need\": Watch The Lyric Video|publisher=Idolator|date=25 June 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730080425/http://idolator.com/7466499/adam-j-sugababes-amelle-berrabah-love-is-all-we-need-lyric-video|archivedate=30 July 2013}}</ref> Berrabah released another single, \"Summertime\", on 21 September 2014. The video premi\u00e8red on Vevo on 9 August.  During this time, Berrabah also made a series of appearances on reality competitions, competing in the BBC celebrity gymnastics show ''[[Tumble (TV series)|Tumble]]'' in mid-2014 and ''[[Celebrity Masterchef]]'' in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/music/musicnews/amelle-berrabah-emma-samms-sign-gymnastics-show-486159.html|title=Amelle Berrabah And Emma Samms Sign Up for Gymnastics Show|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108151806/http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/music/musicnews/amelle-berrabah-emma-samms-sign-gymnastics-show-486159.html|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masterchef.com/celebrity-masterchef|title=Welcome to MasterChef UK|website=MasterChef UK|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615032209/http://www.masterchef.com/celebrity-masterchef|archive-date=15 June 2016}}</ref>  She made her theatre debut in 2019, with the [[Nick Winston]]-directed [[jukebox musical]] ''Club Tropicana''.<ref name=\"tropicana\">https://www.thestage.co.uk/features/interviews/2019/sugababes-amelle-berrabah-musical-theatre-club-tropicana/</ref>\n\nBerrabah married Marcio Sousa Rosa on 17 October 2014.<ref name=\"Amelle announces marriage on official twitter.\">https://twitter.com/Amelle_Berrabah/status/523207635190157312</ref> On 25 December 2017, Berrabah revealed on her Twitter account that she is pregnant.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://twitter.com/Amelle_B_SRosa/status/945409454350176257|title=I\u2019m eating for 2! So I get a pass! Lol|last=Martin|first=Lara|date=25 December 2017|work=[[Twitter]]|publisher=[[Amelle]]|access-date=25 December 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426133728/https://twitter.com/Amelle_B_SRosa/status/945409454350176257|archivedate=26 April 2018}}</ref> She gave birth to her first child on 10 June 2018, a daughter named Amirah.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/Amelle_B_SRosa/status/1005818342861664257/photo/1|title=Our daughter... Amirah Hope Sousa Rosa|date=10 June 2018|work=[[Twitter]]|publisher=[[Amelle]]|access-date=10 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"tropicana\" />\n\n==Discography==\n{{see also|Sugababes discography}}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n!colspan=\"3\"| Chart positions\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! width=40|<small> [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]</small><br /><ref name=acharts>{{citation|url=http://acharts.us/song/47180|title=Tinchy Stryder and Amelle Berrabah \u2013 Never Leave You|publisher=\u03b1Charts.us|accessdate=28 January 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904171820/http://acharts.us/song/47180 |archivedate=4 September 2011}}</ref>\n! width=40|<small> [[Irish Singles Chart|IRE]]</small><br /><ref name=acharts/>\n!style=\"width:4em;font-size:85%\"|[[Euro Hot 100|EU]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=the saturdays|chart=all}}|title=Amelle Berrabah > Album & Song Chart History > European Hot 100|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Company|accessdate=15 November 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n|| 2009\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Never Leave You]]\" <small>(with [[Tinchy Stryder]])</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n||''[[Catch 22 (Tinchy Stryder album)|Catch 22]]''\n|-\n|| 2013\n|align=\"left\"|\"[[Love (Is All We Need)]]\" <small>(with Adam J and Nightcrashers)</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n||Non-album single\n|-\n|| 2014\n|align=\"left\"|\"Summertime\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n||TBA\n|-\n|}\n\n===Other appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style